Category:2020 in the Czech Republic|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in Europe]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in Europe]]\n", "name_user": "Cimmerian praetor", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eWeek 16 (13 \u2013 19 April )", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_the_Czech_Republic"}
{"title_page": "To Build a Fire", "text_new": "{{for|the 2016 film|To Build a Fire (2016 film)}}{{Original research|date=May 2019}}{{Infobox short story <!--See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Novels]]-->\n| name                 = To Build a Fire\n| image                = \n| caption              = \n| title_orig           = \n| translator           = \n| author               = [[Jack London]]\n| country              = United States\n| language             = English\n| series               = \n| genre                = Adventure, short story \n| published_in         = \n| publication_type     =\n| publisher            = \n| media_type           = \n| pub_date             = 1902, 1908\n| english_pub_date     = \n| preceded_by          = \n| followed_by          = \n| preceded_by_italics  = \n| followed_by_italics  = \n}}\n\"'''To Build a Fire'''\" is a [[short story]] by American author [[Jack London]]. There are two versions of this story, one published in 1902 and the other in 1908. The story written in 1908 has become an often anthologized classic, while the 1902 story is less well known. The 1908 version is about an unnamed male protagonist who ventures out in the subzero [[boreal forest]] of the [[Yukon|Yukon Territory]]. He is followed by a native dog and is en route to visit his friends\u2014ignoring warnings from an older man [an elder from the Sulphur Creek]<ref name=\":0\">{{cite book |last1=London |first1=Jack |title=To Build a Fire |date=29 May 1902 Hundesohn|url=https://americanenglish.state.gov/files/ae/resource_files/to-build-a-fire.pdf.}}</ref> about the dangers of hiking alone in extreme cold. The protagonist underestimates the harsh conditions and slowly begins to freeze to death. After building a fire and leaving it to continue his journey, he later attempts to build another fails, then tries to kill the dog to gain access to its body heat, but fails to do either. He slips into [[unconsciousness]] and dies of [[hypothermia]].\n\nThe 1902 version describes a similar situation with a different plot. Though the structure and story line are similar in both, in 1902 the weather is not as cold and horrendous, no dog follows the protagonist, the fire is not doused, and the man (named Tom Vincent) suffers only from permanent [[frostbite]] and survives to become a more melancholic but wiser person.\n\nThe 1908 \"To Build a Fire\" is an oft-cited example of the [[naturalism (literature)|naturalist movement]] that portrays the conflict of [[Man vs. Nature|man vs. nature]]. It also reflects what London learned in the [[Yukon Territory]].\n\n==1908 version plot==\nAn unnamed man sets out to hike through the forests bordering the [[Yukon River]] on a winter day whose temperature has fallen to \u221275&nbsp;\u00b0F (\u221259&nbsp;\u00b0C). Having ignored warnings against traveling alone in such conditions, he is accompanied only by a large [[husky]] dog. The animal's instincts warn it about the dangers of the extreme cold, but the dog follows the man unwillingly. As they follow the course of a frozen creek, the man is careful to avoid patches of thin ice hidden by the snow that cover pockets of unfrozen water. His goal is to reach a group of prospectors \"the boys\" at their camp by six o'clock that evening.\n\nAt half past noon, the man stops and builds a fire so he can warm up and eat his lunch. Shortly after resuming his hike, he accidentally breaks through the ice and soaks his feet and lower legs, forcing him to stop and build another fire, this one under a tree in order to dry himself. As he pulls twigs from the brush pile around the tree to feed the flames, the vibrations eventually cause the snow to tumble down from the branches overhead and extinguish the fire. The man quickly begins to lose sensation in his extremities and hurries to light another fire, now starting to understand the warnings about the life-threatening danger posed by the extreme cold. He lights the fire, igniting all of his matches and burning himself in the process due to the numbness in his hands. While trying to remove a piece of moss from the fire, he inadvertently pokes the burning twigs apart and extinguishes them. With no way to start another fire, the man tries to kill the dog and use its body heat to save himself, but his hands are so stiff that he can neither strangle the animal nor draw his knife to cut its throat. Finally, he tries to restore his circulation by running toward the camp, but stumbles and falls multiple times in the snow. The man dies of [[hypothermia]], imagining himself standing with \"the boys\" as they find his body, and the dog leaves the body after dark to find food and shelter at the camp.\n\n==Character relationships==\nThe protagonist and the old man of Sulphur Creek are seen in the beginning of the story. The old man of Sulphur Creek warns the protagonist about the danger of travelling alone in such cold temperatures, but being ignorant the protagonist scoffs at the advice of the old man. The protagonist is seen reflecting on his advice towards his demise, and realizes that the old man of Sulphur Creek was right in his warning.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe man and the dog's relationship is followed throughout the story. The man has strict control of the dog, as explicitly mentioned by London. The dog is almost like the man's slave.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Ulicne|first1=Chris|title=The Unmentioned|url=http://blogs.setonhill.edu/ChristopherUlicne/coursework007137.html|website=Stone Hill College|accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref> The dog is shown cowering before the man and following orders. There is no physical intimacy or compassion between the two. The man does not pet the dog or treat it fondly. In fact, the man forces the dog to go ahead of him when he suspects the ice will break. This helps to build the idea that the man believes nature is intended to serve him.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Fleissner|first1=Jennifer|title=\"To Build a Fire\": An Environmentalist Interpretation|url=http://americainclass.org/to-build-a-fire-an-environmentalist-interpretation/|website=America In Class|accessdate=5 April 2018|date=January 2013}}</ref> The man's interactions in this relationship is how the reader discovers the man's personality and character. By including the dog, the author makes the man less likable. He was cruel towards the dog by having the dog walk in extreme temperatures. Moreover, in the end, he tried to kill the dog for his own benefit. London even describes the dog as his \"toil-slave\".<ref name=\"story\">{{cite magazine|date=August 1908|title=To Build a Fire|volume=76|last=London|first=Jack|magazine=The Century Magazine |pages=525\u2013534 |url=http://london.sonoma.edu/Writings/LostFace/fire.html |access-date=April 16, 2019 |via=London.Sonoma.edu}} Full text of the famous second version, published for an adult audience.</ref>\n\nWhile the man sees the dog only as his slave on the journey, the dog sees the man as a provider of his needs, which helps follow his [[instincts]].{{Citation needed|date=May 2019}} Placing the dog in the story allowed London to show the wisdom of nature over the [[arrogance]] of the man, which eventually leads to his demise. <ref>{{cite magazine |title=\"Never Travel Alone\": Naturalism, Jack London, and the White Silence |author=Jeanne Campbell Reesman |magazine=American Literary Realism, 1870\u20131910 |volume=29 |issue=2 |date=Winter 1997 |pages=33\u201349 |publisher=University of Illinois Press |jstor=27746687 }}</ref> Doing so, allowed London to show that animals survive through instinct. On the other hand, London shows that men who lack that same intellect, such as man in the story, fail and don't survive.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bowen|first=James K.|date=1971|title=Jack London's \"To Build a Fire\": Epistemology and the White Wilderness|journal=Western American Literature|volume=5|issue=4|pages=287\u2013289|issn=0043-3462|jstor=43017420}}</ref>\n\n==Themes==\n\"[[Man vs. Nature]]\" is one of the themes present in this short story. The protagonist decides to face the brutally cold temperatures of the [[Yukon Territory]], despite being warned by an older man. The short story depicts the protagonist's battle of life and death while highlighting the importance of the fire.\n\nOne theme illustrated in the story is the man's sense of judgment contrasted with the dog's animal [[instinct]]s. Throughout the story, London hints that the dog has more knowledge of survival than the man. The judgment-versus-instinct theme is evident when the man builds the first fire. While the dog wants to stay by the fire to keep warm, the man is determined to keep moving. As the dog reluctantly follows the man across a frozen river, the dog is more cautious than the man.\n\nThe protagonist's desperation is evident throughout the majority of the story. It is noticeable soon after the man falls into a frozen-over river. In order to save himself, he scrambles to build a fire but is too busy worrying about his survival to notice the mistake of building a fire underneath a tree which has collected an enormous amount of snow. After the first fire is put out, his desperation becomes more defined as he seemingly will do anything to survive, including attempting to kill his dog for warmth and using all his matches at once in a final attempt to light his last fire. His desperation for survival and his fear of death cause him to panic, leading to his final demise as he freezes to death at the end of the story.<ref name=\"story\" />\n\n\"[[Perseverance (virtue)|Perseverance]]\" Another evident theme in the story is perseverance. Although the man makes several mistakes and is getting frostbite in his fingers and toes, he continues to fight for survival. He ignored all the signs that he would not make it to the village he was headed to. For instance, London described \u201cHe did not bare his fingers more than a minute and was surprised to find that they were numb.\u201d <ref>{{cite book |last1=London |first1=Jack |title=To Build a Fire |date=29 May 1902 |url=https://americanenglish.state.gov/files/ae/resource_files/to-build-a-fire.pdf.}}</ref> In less than 60 seconds his fingers were numb indicating to him that it is too dangerous for him to be outside.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shmoop.com/to-build-a-fire/perseverance-theme.html|title=To Build a Fire Theme of Perseverance|website=www.shmoop.com|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref> \n\n\"[[Wisdom and Experience]]\" Another theme that is present is that of wisdom and experience. London shows us throughout the story that the man lacks the knowledge in order to survive in the Yukon.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Welsh |first1=James |title=Masterplots II: Short Story Series |journal=Revised Edition |date=2004 |volume=1 |pages=1\u20133 |url=http://web.b.ebscohost.com.unh-proxy01.newhaven.edu:2048/lrc/detail/detail?vid=6&sid=2ee11b99-9eb2-45d3-9942-5949eaec8c5a%40pdc-v-sessmgr03&bdata=JnNpdGU9bHJjLWxpdmU%3d#AN=103331MSS23119240001174&db=lfh |accessdate=16 April 2019}}</ref> Based on instincts, the dog knew that it was too cold to travel in the snow. London wrote: \u201cThe dog was sorry to leave and looked toward the fire.\u201d<ref>{{cite book |last1=London |first1=Jack |title=\"To Build a Fire\" |date=29 May 1902 |url=https://americanenglish.state.gov/files/ae/resource_files/to-build-a-fire.pdf.}}</ref> This line indicates that the dog wanted to be closer to heat. However, the unnamed protagonist ignored all the signs before him. He knew that it was cold but he did not realize the threat this posed on his life.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shmoop.com/to-build-a-fire/themes.html|title=To Build a Fire Themes|website=www.shmoop.com|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref> \n\nStupidity and arrogance are personified in the story's protagonist. For example, he goes through the extremely cold territory alone, despite going for the first time. He laughs off the crucial advice from the old man of Sulphur Creek about traveling with an acquaintance because he thinks he knows what he's doing. This arrogance results in the protagonist putting himself in a dangerous situation that was preventable. At first, he thinks it's nothing and that everything will be fine. By the end of the story, he dies as a result of his arrogance. Through this story, London shows how the man's demise is due to his humanity and lack of thought when going into this journey. Also, he shows that the dog survives because of following its instincts which is something that the man does not pay attention to.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Bowen |first1=James |title='To Build a Fire': Epistemology and the White Wilderness |journal=Western American Literature |date=1971 |volume=5 |issue=4 |pages=287\u2013289|doi=10.1353/wal.1971.0004 }}</ref> Another example of arrogance occurs when the protagonist disregards the possibility that there may be situations he cannot overcome. The old man warns the protagonist of this and also seems to have a better understanding of the natural world, respecting the fact that there are some situations the man will be unable to control. Not only does the old man see the protagonist's stupidity, but the dog notices the man's lack of knowledge about the terrain and its obstacles after he fails to keep a fire going.\n\nSuccumbing to death is another theme in the story: more specifically the peace that may be found in death. London foreshadows the death of the man early in the story, so it is not a surprise that the man dies. However, London depicts death quite differently than many other authors do. The man drifts off into a calm, peaceful slumber devoid of suffering and pain. London's use of relaxing words dissuades the reader from feeling a great deal of sympathy for the man, as the death is merciful and graciously anticipated, rather than sad. In contrast to more dramatic depictions of death, London's depiction reveals death as a peaceful escape from tumult and pain.\n\nIndividualism is another common theme London portrays in the story. The man only relies on himself to get him through the Yukon; he doesn't believe that he needs any help. This theme can also be connected to the theme mentioned above of the man's judgment, and the man's arrogance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://commons.lib.jmu.edu/cgi/cview.cgi/jmurj/vol4/iss1/7|title=James Madison University \u2013 Log in |publisher=Berkeley Electronic Press |website=commons.lib.jmu.edu |url-access=registration |access-date=2018-04-10}}</ref>\n\n==1902 version==\nThe earlier version was first published in ''[[The Youth's Companion]]'' on May 29, 1902.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=London |first=Jack |title=To Build a Fire |url=http://london.sonoma.edu/writings/Uncollected/tobuildafire.html |magazine=Youth's Companion |volume=76 |date=May 29, 1902 |access-date=April 16, 2019 |via=London.Sonoma.edu}} Full text of the first, more juvenile version.</ref> Although it differs in some details, the general structure and storyline are similar; the primary differences are as follows: in the first version it is not as cold, there is no dog, the fire is not doused, and the man (named Tom Vincent) suffers some permanent frostbite damage but survives, sad but wiser.\n\n==Films==\n*''[[:fr:Construire un feu (film, 1928)|Construire un feu]]'' (1927\u20131928) is an early short film by [[Claude Autant-Lara]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.unifrance.org/film/34430/construire-un-feu |title=Construire un feu |language=fr |website=UNIFRANCE |access-date=2019-04-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0019787/combined |title=Construire un feu (1930) |website=Internet Movie Database}}</ref> \n*''To Build a Fire'' (1969) was made by [[David Cobham]], with [[Ian Hogg (actor)|Ian Hogg]] as the man and [[Orson Welles]] as the narrator.<ref name=\"Yahoo\">{{cite web |url=https://movies.yahoo.com/movie/1800395257/info |title=To Build a Fire (1969) |website=Yahoo! Movies |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060516065946/https://movies.yahoo.com/movie/1800395257/info |archive-date=2006-05-16}}</ref> \n*''To Build a Fire'' (2003) is a French version starring Olivier Pag\u00e8s.<ref name=IMDB2003>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0387635/ |title=To Build a Fire (2003) |website=Internet Movie Database}}</ref>\n* ''Build a Fire'' (2011) is an American version with a modified story.<ref name=IMDB2011>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt2572904/ |title=Build a Fire (2011) |website=Internet Movie Database}}</ref> \n* ''[[To Build a Fire (2016 film)|To Build a Fire]]'' (2016) is an animated short film directed by [[Fx Goby]].<ref name=AnimatedShort>{{cite web |url=https://www.indiegogo.com/projects/to-build-a-fire--2#/ |title=To Build a Fire |author=Samuel Fran\u00e7ois-Steininger |website=Indiegogo |access-date=2019-04-17}}</ref>\n* ''COLD'' (2015) is a Spanish short film based on this story.[https://vimeo.com/123391814]\n\n==See also==\n*\"[[The Little Match Girl]],\" a short story by Hans Christian Andersen about a child dying of hypothermia\n*\"[[The Beggar Boy at Christ's Christmas Tree]]\" (1876), a short story by [[Fyodor Dostoevsky]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikisource}}\n* {{librivox book | title=To Build a Fire | author=Jack London}}\n* [https://www.thefreshreads.com/to-build-a-fire/ To Build a Fire by Jack London]\n\n{{Short stories by Jack London}}\n\n[[Category:1902 short stories]]\n[[Category:1908 short stories]]\n[[Category:Short stories adapted into films]]\n[[Category:Short stories by Jack London]]\n[[Category:Yukon in fiction]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the 2016 film|To Build a Fire (2016 film)}}{{Original research|date=May 2019}}{{Infobox short story <!--See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Novels]]-->\n| name                 = To Build a Fire\n| image                = \n| caption              = \n| title_orig           = \n| translator           = \n| author               = [[Jack London]]\n| country              = United States\n| language             = English\n| series               = \n| genre                = Adventure, short story \n| published_in         = \n| publication_type     =\n| publisher            = \n| media_type           = \n| pub_date             = 1902, 1908\n| english_pub_date     = \n| preceded_by          = \n| followed_by          = \n| preceded_by_italics  = \n| followed_by_italics  = \n}}\n\"'''To Build a Fire'''\" is a [[short story]] by American author [[Jack London]]. There are two versions of this story, one published in 1902 and the other in 1908. The story written in 1908 has become an often anthologized classic, while the 1902 story is less well known. The 1908 version is about an unnamed male protagonist who ventures out in the subzero [[boreal forest]] of the [[Yukon|Yukon Territory]]. He is followed by a native dog and is en route to visit his friends\u2014ignoring warnings from an older man [an elder from the Sulphur Creek]<ref name=\":0\">{{cite book |last1=London |first1=Jack |title=To Build a Fire |date=29 May 1902 Hundesohn|url=https://americanenglish.state.gov/files/ae/resource_files/to-build-a-fire.pdf.}}</ref> about the dangers of hiking alone in extreme cold. The protagonist underestimates the harsh conditions and slowly begins to freeze to death. After building a fire and leaving it to continue his journey, he later attempts to build another fails, then tries to kill the dog to gain access to its body heat, but fails to do either. He slips into [[unconsciousness]] and dies of [[hypothermia]].\n\nThe 1902 version describes a similar situation with a different plot. Though the structure and story line are similar in both, in 1902 the weather is not as cold and horrendous, no dog follows the protagonist, the fire is not doused, and the man (named Tom Vincent) suffers only from permanent [[frostbite]] and survives to become a more melancholic but wiser person.\n\nThe 1908 \"To Build a Fire\" is an oft-cited example of the [[naturalism (literature)|naturalist movement]] that portrays the conflict of [[Man vs. Nature|man vs. nature]]. It also reflects what London learned in the [[Yukon Territory]].\n\n==1908 version plot==\nAn unnamed man sets out to hike through the forests bordering the [[Yukon River]] on a winter day whose temperature has fallen to \u221275&nbsp;\u00b0F (\u221259&nbsp;\u00b0C). Having ignored warnings against traveling alone in such conditions, he is accompanied only by a large [[husky]] dog. The animal's instincts warn it about the dangers of the extreme cold, but the dog follows the man unwillingly. As they follow the course of a frozen creek, the man is careful to avoid patches of thin ice hidden by the snow that cover pockets of unfrozen water. His goal is to reach a group of prospectors \"the boys\" at their camp by six o'clock that evening.\n\nAt half past noon, the man stops and builds a fire so he can warm up and eat his lunch. Shortly after resuming his hike, he accidentally breaks through the ice and soaks his feet and lower legs, forcing him to stop and build another fire\u2014this one under a tree\u2014in order to dry himself. As he pulls twigs from the brush pile around the tree to feed the flames, the vibrations eventually cause the snow to tumble down from the branches overhead and extinguish the fire. The man quickly begins to lose sensation in his extremities and hurries to light another fire, now starting to understand the warnings about the life-threatening danger posed by the extreme cold. He lights the fire, igniting all of his matches and burning himself in the process due to the numbness in his hands. While trying to remove a piece of moss from the fire, he inadvertently pokes the burning twigs apart and extinguishes them. With no way to start another fire, the man tries to kill the dog and use its body heat to save himself, but his hands are so stiff that he can neither strangle the animal nor draw his knife to cut its throat. Finally, he tries to restore his circulation by running toward the camp, but stumbles and falls multiple times in the snow. The man dies of [[hypothermia]], imagining himself standing with \"the boys\" as they find his body, and the dog leaves the body after dark to find food and shelter at the camp.\n\n==Character relationships==\nThe protagonist and the old man of Sulphur Creek are seen in the beginning of the story. The old man of Sulphur Creek warns the protagonist about the danger of travelling alone in such cold temperatures, but being ignorant the protagonist scoffs at the advice of the old man. The protagonist is seen reflecting on his advice towards his demise, and realizes that the old man of Sulphur Creek was right in his warning.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe man and the dog's relationship is followed throughout the story. The man has strict control of the dog, as explicitly mentioned by London. The dog is almost like the man's slave.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Ulicne|first1=Chris|title=The Unmentioned|url=http://blogs.setonhill.edu/ChristopherUlicne/coursework007137.html|website=Stone Hill College|accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref> The dog is shown cowering before the man and following orders. There is no physical intimacy or compassion between the two. The man does not pet the dog or treat it fondly. In fact, the man forces the dog to go ahead of him when he suspects the ice will break. This helps to build the idea that the man believes nature is intended to serve him.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Fleissner|first1=Jennifer|title=\"To Build a Fire\": An Environmentalist Interpretation|url=http://americainclass.org/to-build-a-fire-an-environmentalist-interpretation/|website=America In Class|accessdate=5 April 2018|date=January 2013}}</ref> The man's interactions in this relationship is how the reader discovers the man's personality and character. By including the dog, the author makes the man less likable. He was cruel towards the dog by having the dog walk in extreme temperatures. Moreover, in the end, he tried to kill the dog for his own benefit. London even describes the dog as his \"toil-slave\".<ref name=\"story\">{{cite magazine|date=August 1908|title=To Build a Fire|volume=76|last=London|first=Jack|magazine=The Century Magazine |pages=525\u2013534 |url=http://london.sonoma.edu/Writings/LostFace/fire.html |access-date=April 16, 2019 |via=London.Sonoma.edu}} Full text of the famous second version, published for an adult audience.</ref>\n\nWhile the man sees the dog only as his slave on the journey, the dog sees the man as a provider of his needs, which helps follow his [[instincts]].{{Citation needed|date=May 2019}} Placing the dog in the story allowed London to show the wisdom of nature over the [[arrogance]] of the man, which eventually leads to his demise. <ref>{{cite magazine |title=\"Never Travel Alone\": Naturalism, Jack London, and the White Silence |author=Jeanne Campbell Reesman |magazine=American Literary Realism, 1870\u20131910 |volume=29 |issue=2 |date=Winter 1997 |pages=33\u201349 |publisher=University of Illinois Press |jstor=27746687 }}</ref> Doing so, allowed London to show that animals survive through instinct. On the other hand, London shows that men who lack that same intellect, such as man in the story, fail and don't survive.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bowen|first=James K.|date=1971|title=Jack London's \"To Build a Fire\": Epistemology and the White Wilderness|journal=Western American Literature|volume=5|issue=4|pages=287\u2013289|issn=0043-3462|jstor=43017420}}</ref>\n\n==Themes==\n\"[[Man vs. Nature]]\" is one of the themes present in this short story. The protagonist decides to face the brutally cold temperatures of the [[Yukon Territory]], despite being warned by an older man. The short story depicts the protagonist's battle of life and death while highlighting the importance of the fire.\n\nOne theme illustrated in the story is the man's sense of judgment contrasted with the dog's animal [[instinct]]s. Throughout the story, London hints that the dog has more knowledge of survival than the man. The judgment-versus-instinct theme is evident when the man builds the first fire. While the dog wants to stay by the fire to keep warm, the man is determined to keep moving. As the dog reluctantly follows the man across a frozen river, the dog is more cautious than the man.\n\nThe protagonist's desperation is evident throughout the majority of the story. It is noticeable soon after the man falls into a frozen-over river. In order to save himself, he scrambles to build a fire but is too busy worrying about his survival to notice the mistake of building a fire underneath a tree which has collected an enormous amount of snow. After the first fire is put out, his desperation becomes more defined as he seemingly will do anything to survive, including attempting to kill his dog for warmth and using all his matches at once in a final attempt to light his last fire. His desperation for survival and his fear of death cause him to panic, leading to his final demise as he freezes to death at the end of the story.<ref name=\"story\" />\n\n\"[[Perseverance (virtue)|Perseverance]]\" Another evident theme in the story is perseverance. Although the man makes several mistakes and is getting frostbite in his fingers and toes, he continues to fight for survival. He ignored all the signs that he would not make it to the village he was headed to. For instance, London described \u201cHe did not bare his fingers more than a minute and was surprised to find that they were numb.\u201d <ref>{{cite book |last1=London |first1=Jack |title=To Build a Fire |date=29 May 1902 |url=https://americanenglish.state.gov/files/ae/resource_files/to-build-a-fire.pdf.}}</ref> In less than 60 seconds his fingers were numb indicating to him that it is too dangerous for him to be outside.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shmoop.com/to-build-a-fire/perseverance-theme.html|title=To Build a Fire Theme of Perseverance|website=www.shmoop.com|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref> \n\n\"[[Wisdom and Experience]]\" Another theme that is present is that of wisdom and experience. London shows us throughout the story that the man lacks the knowledge in order to survive in the Yukon.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Welsh |first1=James |title=Masterplots II: Short Story Series |journal=Revised Edition |date=2004 |volume=1 |pages=1\u20133 |url=http://web.b.ebscohost.com.unh-proxy01.newhaven.edu:2048/lrc/detail/detail?vid=6&sid=2ee11b99-9eb2-45d3-9942-5949eaec8c5a%40pdc-v-sessmgr03&bdata=JnNpdGU9bHJjLWxpdmU%3d#AN=103331MSS23119240001174&db=lfh |accessdate=16 April 2019}}</ref> Based on instincts, the dog knew that it was too cold to travel in the snow. London wrote: \u201cThe dog was sorry to leave and looked toward the fire.\u201d<ref>{{cite book |last1=London |first1=Jack |title=\"To Build a Fire\" |date=29 May 1902 |url=https://americanenglish.state.gov/files/ae/resource_files/to-build-a-fire.pdf.}}</ref> This line indicates that the dog wanted to be closer to heat. However, the unnamed protagonist ignored all the signs before him. He knew that it was cold but he did not realize the threat this posed on his life.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shmoop.com/to-build-a-fire/themes.html|title=To Build a Fire Themes|website=www.shmoop.com|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref> \n\nStupidity and arrogance are personified in the story's protagonist. For example, he goes through the extremely cold territory alone, despite going for the first time. He laughs off the crucial advice from the old man of Sulphur Creek about traveling with an acquaintance because he thinks he knows what he's doing. This arrogance results in the protagonist putting himself in a dangerous situation that was preventable. At first, he thinks it's nothing and that everything will be fine. By the end of the story, he dies as a result of his arrogance. Through this story, London shows how the man's demise is due to his humanity and lack of thought when going into this journey. Also, he shows that the dog survives because of following its instincts which is something that the man does not pay attention to.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Bowen |first1=James |title='To Build a Fire': Epistemology and the White Wilderness |journal=Western American Literature |date=1971 |volume=5 |issue=4 |pages=287\u2013289|doi=10.1353/wal.1971.0004 }}</ref> Another example of arrogance occurs when the protagonist disregards the possibility that there may be situations he cannot overcome. The old man warns the protagonist of this and also seems to have a better understanding of the natural world, respecting the fact that there are some situations the man will be unable to control. Not only does the old man see the protagonist's stupidity, but the dog notices the man's lack of knowledge about the terrain and its obstacles after he fails to keep a fire going.\n\nSuccumbing to death is another theme in the story: more specifically the peace that may be found in death. London foreshadows the death of the man early in the story, so it is not a surprise that the man dies. However, London depicts death quite differently than many other authors do. The man drifts off into a calm, peaceful slumber devoid of suffering and pain. London's use of relaxing words dissuades the reader from feeling a great deal of sympathy for the man, as the death is merciful and graciously anticipated, rather than sad. In contrast to more dramatic depictions of death, London's depiction reveals death as a peaceful escape from tumult and pain.\n\nIndividualism is another common theme London portrays in the story. The man only relies on himself to get him through the Yukon; he doesn't believe that he needs any help. This theme can also be connected to the theme mentioned above of the man's judgment, and the man's arrogance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://commons.lib.jmu.edu/cgi/cview.cgi/jmurj/vol4/iss1/7|title=James Madison University \u2013 Log in |publisher=Berkeley Electronic Press |website=commons.lib.jmu.edu |url-access=registration |access-date=2018-04-10}}</ref>\n\n==1902 version==\nThe earlier version was first published in ''[[The Youth's Companion]]'' on May 29, 1902.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=London |first=Jack |title=To Build a Fire |url=http://london.sonoma.edu/writings/Uncollected/tobuildafire.html |magazine=Youth's Companion |volume=76 |date=May 29, 1902 |access-date=April 16, 2019 |via=London.Sonoma.edu}} Full text of the first, more juvenile version.</ref> Although it differs in some details, the general structure and storyline are similar; the primary differences are as follows: in the first version it is not as cold, there is no dog, the fire is not doused, and the man (named Tom Vincent) suffers some permanent frostbite damage but survives, sad but wiser.\n\n==Films==\n*''[[:fr:Construire un feu (film, 1928)|Construire un feu]]'' (1927\u20131928) is an early short film by [[Claude Autant-Lara]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.unifrance.org/film/34430/construire-un-feu |title=Construire un feu |language=fr |website=UNIFRANCE |access-date=2019-04-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0019787/combined |title=Construire un feu (1930) |website=Internet Movie Database}}</ref> \n*''To Build a Fire'' (1969) was made by [[David Cobham]], with [[Ian Hogg (actor)|Ian Hogg]] as the man and [[Orson Welles]] as the narrator.<ref name=\"Yahoo\">{{cite web |url=https://movies.yahoo.com/movie/1800395257/info |title=To Build a Fire (1969) |website=Yahoo! Movies |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060516065946/https://movies.yahoo.com/movie/1800395257/info |archive-date=2006-05-16}}</ref> \n*''To Build a Fire'' (2003) is a French version starring Olivier Pag\u00e8s.<ref name=IMDB2003>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0387635/ |title=To Build a Fire (2003) |website=Internet Movie Database}}</ref>\n* ''Build a Fire'' (2011) is an American version with a modified story.<ref name=IMDB2011>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt2572904/ |title=Build a Fire (2011) |website=Internet Movie Database}}</ref> \n* ''[[To Build a Fire (2016 film)|To Build a Fire]]'' (2016) is an animated short film directed by [[Fx Goby]].<ref name=AnimatedShort>{{cite web |url=https://www.indiegogo.com/projects/to-build-a-fire--2#/ |title=To Build a Fire |author=Samuel Fran\u00e7ois-Steininger |website=Indiegogo |access-date=2019-04-17}}</ref>\n* ''COLD'' (2015) is a Spanish short film based on this story.[https://vimeo.com/123391814]\n\n==See also==\n*\"[[The Little Match Girl]],\" a short story by Hans Christian Andersen about a child dying of hypothermia\n*\"[[The Beggar Boy at Christ's Christmas Tree]]\" (1876), a short story by [[Fyodor Dostoevsky]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikisource}}\n* {{librivox book | title=To Build a Fire | author=Jack London}}\n* [https://www.thefreshreads.com/to-build-a-fire/ To Build a Fire by Jack London]\n\n{{Short stories by Jack London}}\n\n[[Category:1902 short stories]]\n[[Category:1908 short stories]]\n[[Category:Short stories adapted into films]]\n[[Category:Short stories by Jack London]]\n[[Category:Yukon in fiction]]\n", "name_user": "Jnewts99", "label": "safe", "comment": "Punctuation changes", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/To_Build_a_Fire"}
{"title_page": "Jabal Druze State", "text_new": "{{coord missing|Syria}}\n{{Infobox country\n|conventional_long_name = Jabal al-Druze\n|native_name = ''{{lang|fr|Djebel Druze}}''<br>{{lang|ar|\u062c\u0628\u0644 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u0631\u0648\u0632}}\n|common_name = Jabal al-Druze\n|status = League of Nations Mandate\n|empire = France\n|p1 = Kingdom of Syria\n|flag_p1 = Flag of Kingdom of Syria (1920-03-08 to 1920-07-24).svg\n|s1 = Mandatory Syrian Republic\n|flag_s1 = Syria-flag 1932-58 1961-63.svg\n|image_flag = Flag of Jabal ad-Druze (state).svg\n|flag = Flag of Syria\n|image_map = French Mandate for Syria and the Lebanon map en.svg\n|image_map_caption = Location of Jabal al-Druze (turquoise-blue) in the [[French Mandate for Syria and the Lebanon|Mandate for Syria and the Lebanon]]\n|capital = [[As-Suwayda]]\n|religion = [[Christianity]]<br>[[Druze]]<br>[[Sunni Islam]] \n|common_languages = [[French language|French]]<br/>[[Arabic language|Arabic]]\n|representative1 = Prince Salim Basha al-Atrash\n|year_representative1 = 1921&ndash;1923\n|representative2 = Tarit\n|year_representative2 = 1925&ndash;1936\n|era = Interwar period\n|year_start = 1921\n|event1 = {{nowrap|Named \"State of Souaida\"}}\n|date_event1 = 4 March 1922\n|event2 = Named \"Jabal al-Druze\"\n|date_event2 = 1927\n|year_end = 1936\n}}\n\n'''Jabal al-Druze''' ({{lang-ar|\u062c\u0628\u0644 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u0631\u0648\u0632}}, {{lang-fr|Djebel Druze}}) was an autonomous state in the [[French Mandate of Syria]] from 1921 to 1936, designed to function as a government for the local [[Druze]] population under French oversight.\n\n== Nomenclature ==\n{{multiple image\n|align=left\n|image1=Arrete No. 1343 borders of the State of Jebel Druze, March 1922.png\n|caption1=Arrete No. 1343, which laid out the borders of the State of Jebel Druze, March 1922\n|image2=Statut Organique of the State of Jebel Druze 14 May 1930.png\n|caption2=Statut Organique of the State of Jebel Druze, 14 May 1930\n}}\n\nOn March 4, 1922, it was proclaimed as the '''State of Souaida''', after the capital [[As-Suwayda]], but in 1927 it was renamed '''Jabal al-Druze''' or '''Jabal Druze State'''. The name comes from the [[Jabal al-Druze]] mountain.\n\n== History ==\n{{Druze|History}}\nThe Druze state was formed on May 1, 1921, in former [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] territory, while other statelets were installed in other parts of the Syrian mandate (e.g. the [[Alawite State]] in the [[Lattakia]] region). Jabal al-Druze was home to about 50,000 Druze. It was the first, and remains the only, autonomous entity to be populated and governed by Druze. The 1925 [[Great Syrian Revolt|Syrian Revolution]] began in Jabal al-Druze under the leadership of [[Sultan al-Atrash]], and quickly spread to [[Damascus]] and other non-Druze areas outside the [[Jabal al-Druze]] region. Protests against the division of Syrian territory into statelets were a main theme of Syrian [[colonialism|anti-colonial]] nationalism, which eventually won the victory to reunite the entire French-mandated territory, except [[Lebanon]] (which had become independent) and [[Alexandretta]], which was annexed to Turkey as the [[Hatay Province]].\n\nAs a result of [[Syrian nationalist]] pressure, under the [[Franco-Syrian Treaty of Independence (1936)|Franco-Syrian Treaty]] of 1936, Jabal al-Druze ceased to exist as an autonomous entity and was incorporated into [[Mandatory Syrian Republic|Syria]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- \n|+ General distribution of population in the State of Jabal Druze according to the French census in 1921\u201322<ref>E.J. Brill's first encyclopaedia of Islam, 1913-1936, Volume 2, page 301.</ref>\n|-\n! Religion\n! Inhabitants\n! Percentage\n|-\n| [[Druze]] || 43,000 || 84.8%\n|-\n| [[Christians]] || 7,000 || 13.8%\n|-\n| [[Sunni]] || 700 || 1.4%\n|-\n| Total || 50,700 || 100%\n|-\n|}\n\n<gallery widths=\"260px\" heights=\"200px\">\nFile:Druzeindependance1925.jpg|Druze celebrating their independence in 1925\n</gallery>\n\n== Governors ==\n*Amir Salim Pasha al-Atrash (May 1, 1921 \u2013 September 15, 1923)\n*Trenga (provisional) (September 1923 \u2013 March 6, 1924)\n*Gabriel Marie Victor Carbillet (March 6, 1924 \u2013 October 14, 1925), provisional to October 1, 1924\n*[[Sultan Pasha al-Atrash]] (July 18, 1925 \u2013 June 1, 1927), chief of state; in dissidence\n*Charles Andr\u00e9a (October 15, 1925 \u2013 1927)\n*Marie Joseph L\u00e9on Augustin Henry (1927)\n*Abel Jean Ernest Cl\u00e9ment-Grancourt (1927\u20131932)\n*Claude-Gabriel-Renaud Massiet (February 3, 1932 \u2013 January 28, 1934)\n*Justin-Antoine Devicq (1934\u20131935)\n*Pierre-Joseph-Fran\u00e7ois Tarrit (1935 \u2013 December 2, 1936)<ref>[http://www.archontology.org/nations/syria/jabal_druze/00_1921_1936_s.php Jabal Druze: Heads of State: 1921\u20131936]</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Druze in Syria]]\n*[[Jaysh al-Muwahhideen]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.worldstatesmen.org/Syria.html#Jebel%20Druze Syria] at WorldStatesmen.org.\n*[http://unimaps.com/syria-leb1923/mainmap.gif Map] at unimaps.com.\n\n{{French Mandate of Syria}}\n{{Former French colonies}}\n\n[[Category:French Mandate for Syria and the Lebanon]]\n[[Category:Former countries in the Middle East]]\n[[Category:Former protectorates]]\n[[Category:Druze]]\n[[Category:States and territories established in 1921]]\n[[Category:States and territories disestablished in 1936]]\n[[Category:Former polities of the interwar period]]\n[[Category:1936 disestablishments in Asia]]\n[[Category:1921 establishments in Asia]]\n", "text_old": "{{coord missing|Syria}}\n{{Infobox country\n|conventional_long_name = Jabal al-Druze\n|native_name = ''{{lang|fr|Djebel Druze}}''<br>{{lang|ar|\u062c\u0628\u0644 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u0631\u0648\u0632}}\n|common_name = Jabal al-Druze\n|status = League of Nations Mandate\n|empire = France\n|p1 = Kingdom of Syria\n|flag_p1 = Flag of Kingdom of Syria (1920-03-08 to 1920-07-24).svg\n|s1 = Mandatory Syrian Republic\n|flag_s1 = Syria-flag 1932-58 1961-63.svg\n|image_flag = Flag of Jabal ad-Druze (state).svg\n|flag = Flag of Syria\n|image_map = French Mandate for Syria and the Lebanon map en.svg\n|image_map_caption = Location of Jabal al-Druze (turquoise-blue) in the [[French Mandate for Syria and the Lebanon|Mandate for Syria and the Lebanon]]\n|capital = [[As-Suwayda]]\n|religion = [[Christianity]]<br>[[Druze]]<br>[[Sunni Islam]] \n|common_languages = [[French language|French]]<br/>[[Arabic language|Arabic]]\n|representative1 = Prince Salim Basha al-Atrash\n|year_representative1 = 1921&ndash;1923\n|representative2 = Tarit\n|year_representative2 = 1925&ndash;1936\n|era = Interwar period\n|year_start = 1921\n|event1 = {{nowrap|Named \"State of Souaida\"}}\n|date_event1 = 4 March 1922\n|event2 = Named \"Jabal al-Druze\"\n|date_event2 = 1927\n|year_end = 1936\n}}\n\n'''Jabal al-Druze''' ({{lang-ar|\u062c\u0628\u0644 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u0631\u0648\u0632}}, {{lang-fr|Djebel Druze}}) was an autonomous state in the [[French Mandate of Syria]] from 1921 to 1936, designed to function as a government for the local [[Druze]] population under French oversight.\n\n== Nomenclature ==\n{{multiple image\n|align=left\n|image1=Arrete No. 1343 borders of the State of Jebel Druze, March 1922.png\n|caption1=Arrete No. 1343, which laid out the borders of the State of Jebel Druze, March 1922\n|image2=Statut Organique of the State of Jebel Druze 14 May 1930.png\n|caption2=Statut Organique of the State of Jebel Druze, 14 May 1930\n}}\n\nOn March 4, 1922, it was proclaimed as the '''State of Souaida''', after the capital [[As-Suwayda]], but in 1927 it was renamed '''Jabal al-Druze''' or '''Jabal Druze State'''. The name comes from the [[Jabal al-Druze]] mountain.\n\n== History ==\n{{Druze|History}}\nThe Druze state was formed on May 1, 1921, in former [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] territory, while other statelets were installed in other parts of the Syrian mandate (e.g. the [[Alawite State]] in the [[Lattakia]] region). Jabal al-Druze was home to about 50,000 Druze. It was the first, and remains the only, autonomous entity to be populated and governed by Druze. The 1925 [[Great Syrian Revolt|Syrian Revolution]] began in Jabal al-Druze under the leadership of [[Sultan al-Atrash]], and quickly spread to [[Damascus]] and other non-Druze areas outside the [[Jabal al-Druze]] region. Protests against the division of Syrian territory into statelets were a main theme of Syrian [[colonialism|anti-colonial]] nationalism, which eventually won the victory to reunite the entire French-mandated territory, except [[Lebanon]] (which had become independent) and [[Alexandretta]], which was annexed to Turkey as the [[Hatay Province]].\n\nAs a result of [[Syrian nationalist]] pressure, under the [[Franco-Syrian Treaty of Independence (1936)|Franco-Syrian Treaty]] of 1936, Jabal al-Druze ceased to exist as an autonomous entity and was incorporated into [[Mandatory Syrian Republic|Syria]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- \n|+ General distribution of population in the State of Jabal Druze according to the French census in 1921\u201322<ref>E.J. Brill's first encyclopaedia of Islam, 1913-1936, Volume 2, page 301.</ref>\n|-\n! Religion\n! Inhabitants\n! Percentage\n|-\n| [[Druze]] || 43,000 || 84.8%\n|-\n| [[Christians]] || 7,000 || 13.8%\n|-\n| [[Sunni]] || 700 || 1.4%\n|-\n| Total || 50,700 || 100%\n|-\n|}\n\n<gallery widths=\"260px\" heights=\"200px\">\nFile:Druzeindependance1925.jpg|Druze celebrating their independence in 1925\n</gallery>\n\n== Governors ==\n*Amir Salim Pasha al-Atrash (May 1, 1921 - September 15, 1923)\n*Trenga (provisional) (September 1923 - March 6, 1924)\n*Gabriel Marie Victor Carbillet (March 6, 1924 - October 14, 1925), provisional to October 1, 1924\n*[[Sultan Pasha al-Atrash]] (July 18, 1925 - June 1, 1927), chief of state; in dissidence\n*Charles Andr\u00e9a (October 15, 1925 \u2013 1927)\n*Marie Joseph L\u00e9on Augustin Henry (1927)\n*Abel Jean Ernest Cl\u00e9ment-Grancourt (1927\u20131932)\n*Claude-Gabriel-Renaud Massiet (February 3, 1932 - January 28, 1934)\n*Justin-Antoine Devicq (1934\u20131935)\n*Pierre-Joseph-Fran\u00e7ois Tarrit (1935 - December 2, 1936) <ref>[http://www.archontology.org/nations/syria/jabal_druze/00_1921_1936_s.php Jabal Druze: Heads of State: 1921-1936]</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Druze in Syria]]\n*[[Jaysh al-Muwahhideen]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.worldstatesmen.org/Syria.html#Jebel%20Druze Syria] at WorldStatesmen.org.\n*[http://unimaps.com/syria-leb1923/mainmap.gif Map] at unimaps.com.\n\n{{French Mandate of Syria}}\n{{Former French colonies}}\n\n[[Category:French Mandate for Syria and the Lebanon]]\n[[Category:Former countries in the Middle East]]\n[[Category:Former protectorates]]\n[[Category:Druze]]\n[[Category:States and territories established in 1921]]\n[[Category:States and territories disestablished in 1936]]\n[[Category:Former polities of the interwar period]]\n[[Category:1936 disestablishments in Asia]]\n[[Category:1921 establishments in Asia]]\n", "name_user": "Jprg1966", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eGovernors", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jabal_Druze_State"}
{"title_page": "Jack Pleis", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Jack Pleis\n| image               = JackPleis.jpg\n| image_size          = \n| alt                 = \n| caption             = Pleis, on the back cover of<br/>'''''Strings and Things''''' (1957)\n| background          = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_date          = {{birth date|1917|05|11}}<ref name=\"IMDb\">{{IMDb name|0687132}}</ref>\n| birth_place         = [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]], USA\n| origin              = \n| death_date          = {{death date and age|1990|12|05|1917|05|11}}\n| death_place         = [[Palm Springs, California|Palm Springs]], [[California]], USA\n| genre               = Jazz, easy listening\n| occupation          = Pianist, arranger, conductor, composer, producer\n| instrument          = Piano\n| years_active        = 1939\u20131976\n| label               = [[London Records]]<br/>[[Decca Records]]<br/>[[Columbia Records]]\n| associated_acts     = [[Jan Savitt & the Top Hatters]], Jack Pleis Trio, Jack Pleis and His Orchestra, [[Eartha Kitt]], [[Carmen McRae]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Carmen McRae Issues |url=http://www.carmenmcraediscography.com/issues.html |work=CarmenMcRaeDiscography.com |date=August 22, 2006 |accessdate=March 3, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150206104543/http://carmenmcraediscography.com/issues.html |archive-date=February 6, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> [[Henri Ren\u00e9]]\n}}\n'''Jack K. Pleis''' (May 11, 1917 \u2013 December 5, 1990<ref name=\"IMDb\"/>) was an American jazz pianist, arranger, conductor, composer and producer. He recorded on [[London Records|London]] and [[Decca Records]] in the 1950s, and [[Columbia Records]] in the 1960s. During the course of his career, Pleis worked with many artists, including [[Louis Armstrong]], [[Harry Belafonte]],  [[Bing Crosby]], [[Sammy Davis Jr.]], [[Benny Goodman]], [[Earl Grant]], [[Brenda Lee]], and [[Joseph G. Williams|Joe Williams]].<ref name=\"Musiker\"/> Between 1950 and 1976, over 150 songs were arranged by Pleis.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.45cat.com/45_arranger.php?ta=Jack+Pleis |title=Tracks Arranged By: Jack Pleis |work=45cat.com |accessdate=2015-04-10}}</ref> His surname is pronounced \"Pleece\" (to rhyme with \"fleece\").<ref>{{cite book|last1=Pleis|first1=Jack|title=1955 Decca artist sampler interview LP|date=1955}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nPleis was born in [[Philadelphia]] on May 11, 1917. Starting at age four, he began his training in classical piano. He first performed in concert when he was seven. By the time he was eleven, he appeared on radio programs for children.<ref name=\"Musiker\">{{cite book |chapter=Pleis, Jack |title=Conductors and Composers of Popular Orchestral Music: A Biographical and Discographical Sourcebook |first1=Naomi |last1=Musiker |first2=Reuben |last2=Musiker |publisher=Routledge |year=2014 |isbn=9781135917708}}</ref>\n\nPleis enrolled in college intending to study medicine. To support his studies, he played piano in jazz and popular music bands. Eventually he left school and moved to [[New York City]], where he began his musical career.<ref name=\"Musiker\"/>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Early days===\nIn New York, Pleis became successful as a pianist, arranger, conductor, and composer. He was one of [[Jan Savitt]]'s ''Top Hatters'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.discogs.com/artist/335543-Jan-Savitt-And-His-Top-Hatters |title=Jon Savitt And His Top Hatters |work=Discogs |accessdate=2015-04-11}}</ref> playing piano and doing arrangements,<ref>{{cite web |first=Christopher |last=Popa |url=http://www.bigbandlibrary.com/jansavitt.html |title=Jan Savitt: 'The Swing-Happy Years' |work=Big Band Library |date=September 2007 |quote=The tunes recorded in 1941 included a number of classical pieces, such as Prelude to Carmen, The Sorcerer's Apprentice, In the Hall of the Mountain King, and La Cinquantaine, each arranged by Jack Pleis.}}</ref> a position he left in 1942 to enlist in the [[United States Army|Army]] during [[World War II]].<ref>{{cite news |title=News Notes |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=February 21, 1942 |page=61}}</ref> In 1947, the '''Jack Pleis Trio''' provided instrumental support for Larry Laurence (with [[The Quintones]] providing vocal harmonies).<ref>{{cite news |title=Record Reviews |work=Billboard |date=July 5, 1947 |page=131}}</ref> By 1948, Pleis was working at the [[RCA Victor]] studios on [[24th Street (Manhattan)|24th Street]], appearing on the cover of the January 1, 1949 issue of  ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' playing piano at the studio's holiday party.<ref>{{cite news |title=Front cover |work=Billboard |date=January 1, 1949 |page=1 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AhcEAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PP1&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate=2015-04-09}}</ref> His orchestra backed [[Teresa Brewer]] and Bobby Wayne on their 1949 single \"Copper Canyon\"/\"'Way Back Home\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Record Reviews |work=Billboard |date=December 17, 1949 |page=93}}</ref> Pleis was also part of the [[Dixieland All-Stars]] group<ref>{{cite web|title=The Dixieland All Stars|url=https://www.discogs.com/artist/1971661-The-Dixieland-All-Stars|website=Discogs|accessdate=12 May 2017}} (Page names D.A.S. members: \n[[Cutty Cutshall]], Danny Perri, Eddie Safranski, [[Ernie Caceres]], George Wettling, [[Hymie Schertzer]], Jack Pleis, Max Kaminsky, Nick Perito, [[Yank Lawson]]\n)</ref> which backed Brewer's breakout hit (and signature song) [[Music! Music! Music!]] in late 1949.<ref name=\"tbc-l1bdsp\">{{cite web|title=TEENAGE SUCCESS ...the 1940s|url=http://www.teresafans.org/l1bdsp.html|website=Teresa Brewer Center|accessdate=12 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n===London Records===\nPleis joined the  [[American Society of Composers, Authors and Publishers]] (ASCAP) in 1950.<ref name=\"ASCAP\">{{cite book |author=American Society of Composers, Authors and Publishers |chapter=Pleis, Jack K.: composer, conductor |title=The ASCAP biographical dictionary of composers, authors and publishers |edition=3rd |location=New York |publisher=Lynn Farnol Group, Inc. |year=1966}}</ref> He began work as arranger and composer at [[London Records]] under [[Salvatore Camarata|Tutti Camarata]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Camarata, Lewis Set Up London's New A&R Policy |work=Billboard |date=March 4, 1950 |page=15}}</ref> The orchestra backed [[Ralph Young (singer)|Ralph Young]] on his 1950 London single \"Please Treat Her Nicer\"/\"[[I've Got the World on a String]]\",<ref>{{cite news |title=Record Reviews |work=Billboard |date=March 18, 1950 |page=117}}</ref> and Pleis released his own single \"Ragging the Scale\"/\"Story of the Stars\",<ref>{{cite news |title=Record Reviews |work=Billboard |date=March 25, 1950 |page=34}}</ref> the B-side of which ranked at number 10 on \"The Disk Jockeys Pick\" in ''Billboard''.<ref>{{cite news |title=The Disk Jockeys Pick |work=Billboard |date=April 15, 1950 |page=50}}</ref> In early May 1950, he accompanied his future wife, London recording artist [[Eve Young]], on a promotional tour prior to her opening show.<ref>{{cite news |title=Music\u2014As Written |work=Billboard |date=May 13, 1950 |page=20}}</ref> Pleis released several more singles, \"Time Alone (Can Heal a Broken Heart)\"/\"What is There to Say\",<ref>{{cite news |title=Record Reviews |work=Billboard |date=September 30, 1950 |page=99}}</ref> \"I'll Always Be in Love with You\"/\"[[Caravan (1937 song)|Caravan]]\",<ref>{{cite news |title=Record Reviews |work=Billboard |date=November 25, 1950 |page=32}}</ref> and \"Le Petite Valse\"/\"Ragamuffin\", and the orchestra backed [[Snooky Lanson]] on his 1950 London single \"You Wonderful You\"/\"Honestly I Love You\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Record Reviews |work=Billboard |date=August 26, 1950 |pages=33, 94}}</ref>\n\nIn June 1950, Pleis married Eve Young,<ref>{{cite news |title=Lovely Idaho Star Weds Executive Of Music Company |work=[[The Salt Lake Tribune]] |date=July 30, 1950 |page=20}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Music as Written |work=Billboard |date=December 2, 1950 |page=14}}</ref> and the March birth of their daughter Michelle was noted in an April 1951 ''Billboard''.<ref>{{cite news |title=Music as Written |work=Billboard |date=April 28, 1951 |page=18}}</ref> The Orchestra backed Eve on her single \"Just for Tonight\"/\"Would I Love You?\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Record Reviews |work=Billboard |date=January 27, 1951 |page=31}}</ref> In 1952, Pleis and orchestra worked with [[The Bell Sisters]]<ref>{{cite news |title=Record Reviews |work=Billboard |date=October 4, 1952 |page=44}}</ref> and continued working with Teresa Brewer.<ref>{{cite news |title=Record Reviews |work=Billboard |date=November 1, 1952 |page=38}}</ref> Pleis left London Records,<ref name=Decca>{{cite news |title=Decca Adds Jack Pleis to A & R Unit |work=Billboard |date=June 20, 1953 |page=25}}</ref> and Eve signed a new contract with [[Coral Records]], recording under her new name, [[Karen Chandler]].<ref>{{Allmusic | class = artist | id = p185120 | tab = biography | label = Biography of Karen Chandler | first = Jason | last = Ankeny | accessdate = 2015-04-10 }}</ref> Her debut for Coral, backed by Pleis' orchestra, was the song \"[[Hold Me, Thrill Me, Kiss Me]],\" and it became an enormous hit. Selling over a million copies, it peaked at No. 5 on the [[Billboard charts|''Billboard'' charts]]. In 1953, Pleis and orchestra backed her on her third Coral release, \"I'd Love to Fall Asleep (And Wake Up in Your Arms)\"/\"Goodbye, Charlie, Goodbye\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Coral Records advert |work=Billboard |date=March 21, 1953 |page=36 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZEUEAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA36&pg=PA36#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate=2015-04-10}}</ref>\n\n===Decca Records===\nIn mid-1953 Pleis joined [[Decca Records]] under [[Milt Gabler]].<ref name=Decca/> Pleis and Orchestra released \"The Eighteenth Variation\"/\"Mr. Peepers\" under the Decca label.<ref>{{cite news |title=Reviews of this Week's New Records |work=Billboard |date=October 3, 1953 |page=28}}</ref> The orchestra backed Karen Chandler again on \"[[Buddy Feyne|Why?]]\"/\"Flash From the Blue\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Popular Record Reviews |work=Billboard |date=November 14, 1953 |page=50}}</ref> 1954 saw the release of the orchestra's Decca singles, \"Frenchman in St. Louis\"/\"Pagan in Paris\",<ref>{{cite news |title=Review of this Week's New Records |work=Billboard |date=January 23, 1954 |page=24}}</ref> \"Ah Ri Rung\",<ref>{{cite news |title=Music as Written |work=Billboard |date=June 5, 1954 |page=20}}</ref> and \"For Always\"/\"[[Beyond the Blue Horizon (song)|Beyond the Blue Horizon]]\",<ref>{{cite news |title=Reviews of New Pop Records |work=Billboard |date=October 16, 1954 |page=34}}</ref> and the orchestra backed [[the Dinning Sisters]] on \"Steel Guitar Rag\",<ref>{{cite news |title=Popular Record Reviews |work=Billboard |date=January 30, 1954 |page=44}}</ref> [[Eileen Barton]] on \"And Then\",<ref>{{cite news |title=Reviews of New Pop Records |work=Billboard |date=September 25, 1954 |page=54}}</ref> and [[Teresa Brewer]] on her album ''A Bouquet of Hits''.<ref>{{cite news |title=Best Selling Popular Albums |work=Billboard |date=October 23, 1954 |page=22}}</ref>\n\n1955 saw Pleis scheduled to be profiled in the April issue of ''[[The American Magazine]]''.<ref>{{cite news |title=Music as Written |work=Billboard |date=February 26, 1955 |page=34}}</ref> Pleis and His Orchestra began releasing singles of [[The Walt Disney Company|Disney]] film songs (also collected and released on the album ''Music from Disneyland''),<ref>{{cite news |title=Reviews of New Pop Records |work=Billboard |date=March 26, 1955 |page=124}}</ref> and also released \"[[Lies (1931 song)|Lies]]\"/\"[[Hey There]]\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Reviews of New Pop Records |work=Billboard |date=September 10, 1955 |page=40}}</ref> and \"Pauline\"/\"[[The Trouble With Harry#Musical score|The Trouble With Harry]]\", the title tune for [[Alfred Hitchcock]]'s film, ''[[The Trouble with Harry]]''.<ref>{{cite news |title=Popular Records |work=Billboard |date=December 10, 1955 |page=50}}</ref>\n\nIn 1956, Pleis and His Orchestra again backed Karen Chandler, this time on her first Decca release,<ref>{{cite news |title = Decca Records advert |work=Billboard |date=March 17, 1956 |page=45 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8x4EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA45&pg=PA45#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate=2015-04-10}}</ref> and Pleis released another album, ''Strings and Things''.<ref>{{cite news |title=Reviews and Ratings of New Popular Albums |work=Billboard |date=February 2, 1957 |page=30}}</ref> The orchestra backed [[Bobby Darrin]] on his single \"[[Rock Island Line]]\"/\"Timber\".<ref>{{cite book |first=Steve |last=Karmen |title=Me And Bobby D.: A Memoir |publisher=Hal Leonard Corporation |year=2004 |isbn=9780634080265 |page=68}}</ref> In October, Pleiss' song \"Giant\", theme of the film ''[[Giant (1956 film)|Giant]]'', debuted on the [[Billboard charts|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] at #93, peaking at #91 in December,<ref name=\"Giant\">{{cite web |url=http://song-database.com/chhist.php?sid=23146 |title=Billboard Hot 100 Chart History: \"Giant\" |work=Song-database.com |accessdate=2015-04-10}}</ref> and the song \"I'll Always Be In Love With You\" charted at #65, also in December.<ref name=chart2>{{cite web |url=http://www.song-database.com/chhist.php?sid=23147&from=spu&type=ht |title=Billboard Hot 100 Chart History: \"I'll Always Be In Love With You\" |work=Song-database.com |accessdate=2015-04-10}}</ref> Pleis also produced [[Bing Crosby]]'s album, ''[[Songs I Wish I Had Sung the First Time Around]]''.<ref>{{cite book |first=Will |last=Friedwald |title=A Biographical Guide to the Great Jazz and Pop Singers |publisher=Knopf Doubleday Publishing Group |year=2010 |isbn=9780307379894 |page=128}}</ref>\n\n1957 saw the release of singles \"(But As They Say) That's Life\"/\"Goodnight Waltz\",<ref>{{cite news |title=Reviews and Ratings |work=Billboard |date=April 29, 1957 |page=50}}</ref> \"Search for Paradise\"/\"Serenade to Michelle\",<ref>{{cite news |title=Reviews of New Pop Records |work=Billboard |date=September 2, 1957 |page=56}}</ref> and \"The Carefree Heart\"/\"Serenade in Soft Shoe\",<ref>{{cite news |title=Pop Records |work=Billboard |date=October 14, 1957 |page=51}}</ref> and the Orchestra backed [[Georgie Shaw]] on \"[[One More Sunrise]]\", [[Sammy Davis Jr.]] on \"The Golden Key\",<ref>{{cite news |title=Review of New Pop Records |work=Billboard |date=February 9, 1957 |page=49}}</ref> and [[Merv Griffin]] on \"I'll Be Thinking of You\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Reviews of New Pop Records |work=Billboard |date=March 9, 1957 |page=55}}</ref>  \"(But As They Say) That's Life\" charted at #69 in June 1957.<ref name=chart3>{{cite web |url=http://www.song-database.com/chhist.php?sid=23148&from=spu&type=ht |title=Billboard Hot 100 Chart History: \"(But As They Say) That's Life\" |work=Song-database.com |accessdate=2015-04-10}}</ref>\n\nIn 1958, the Orchestra backed [[Carmen McRae]] on her album ''[[Mad About the Man]]'',<ref>{{cite news |title=Reviews and Ratings of New Popular Albums |work=Billboard |date=February 17, 1958 |page=37}}</ref> as well as [[Toni Arden]]<ref>{{cite news |title=Review of New Pop Records |work=Billboard |date=April 7, 1958 |page=50}}</ref> and also backed [[The Four Aces]] on their album ''Swingin{{'}} Aces''.<ref>{{cite news |title=Reviews and Ratings of New Popular Album |work=Billboard |date=November 10, 1958 |page=22}}</ref> He produced the [[Kalin Twins]]{{'}} song \"[[When (The Kalin Twins song)|When]]\", which spent five weeks at No. 1 on the UK charts.<ref>{{cite book |first=Jon |last=Kutner |title=1000 UK Number One Hits |publisher=Omnibus Press |year=2010 |isbn=9780857123602}}</ref>\n\nIn 1960, Pleis conducted for The Castilians' album, ''Valentino Tangos''.<ref>{{cite news |title=Records |work=The Deseret News |date=April 7, 1960 |page=18C}}</ref> Pleis and Orchestra backed [[Sammy Davis Jr.]] on a dozen tracks for Decca, including \"[[What Kind of Fool Am I?]]\" (which won the [[Grammy Award for Song of the Year]] in 1963), \"[[The Lady Is a Tramp]]\", \"[[I Gotta Right to Sing the Blues]]\", \"[[Do Nothing till You Hear from Me|Do Nothin' Till You Hear From Me]]\", \"[[I Got a Woman]]\", \"[[There Is No Greater Love]]\", \"[[Gee, Baby, Ain't I Good to You]]\", \"[[This Little Girl of Mine]]\", \"[[Till Then]]\", and \"[[Mess Around]]\".<ref>{{cite book |first=Marshal |last=Royal |authorlink=Marshal Royal |title=Marshal Royal: Jazz Survivor |publisher=A&C Black |year=2001 |isbn=9780826458049 |page=159}}</ref>\n\n===Columbia Records===\nThe 1960s brought a move to [[Columbia Records]]. In 1961, Pleis and Orchestra backed Brazilian singer [[Maysa Matarazzo]] on her album ''[[:pt:Maysa Sings Songs Before Dawn|Maysa Sings Songs Before Dawn]]'',<ref>{{cite book |first=Lira |last=Neto |title=Maysa: s\u00f3 numa multid\u00e3o de amores |publisher=Editora Globo |year=2007 |isbn=9788525043030 |language=pt |page=156}}</ref> he conducted for [[Billy Butterfield]]'s album, ''The Golden Horn'',<ref name=Chevan>{{cite book |first1=Edward |last1=Berger |first2=David |last2=Chevan |first3=Benny |last3=Carter |title=Bassically Speaking: An Oral History of George Duvivier |publisher=Scarecrow Press |year=1993 |isbn=0810826917 |pages=311, 338}}</ref> and arranged several of the tracks on [[Lionel Hampton]]'s album, ''Soft Vibes Soaring Strings''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.discogs.com/Lionel-Hampton-Soft-Vibes-Soaring-Strings/release/6021195 |title=Lionel Hampton \u2013 ''Soft Vibes Soaring Strings'' |work=Discogs |accessdate=2015-04-11}}</ref>  Pleis also produced [[Les Elgart]]'s album, ''\"It's De-Lovely\" For Dancing and Listening'',<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.discogs.com/Les-Elgart-Its-De-lovely-For-Dancing-And-Listening/release/4139234 | title=Les Elgart - ''\"It's De-Lovely\" For Dancing and Listening'' |work=Discogs |accessdate=2018-04-17}}</ref> and released an EP, ''Medley from The Musical \"Through The Years\"'' and an LP, ''Stage Left, Stage Right''. In 1963, he conducted for [[Peter Nero]]'s album, ''Born Free'',<ref name=Chevan/> and Pleis and Orchestra backed [[Liza Minnelli]] on her single, \"One Summer Love\"/\"How Much Do I Love You?\".<ref>{{cite book |first1=Scott |last1=Schechter |first2=Billy |last2=Stritch |title=The Liza Minnelli Scrapbook |publisher=Citadel Press |year=2004 |isbn=9780806526119 |page=127}}</ref>\n\n===Film and television scores===\nPleis and His Orchestra performed the songs \"Strange Feelings\" and \"The Blues I Got Comin' Tomorrow\" for the soundtrack of the 1961 film, ''Force of Impulse''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0132974/soundtrack?ref_=tt_trv_snd |title=Force of Impulse (1961) \u2014 Soundtracks |work=IMDb |accessdate=2015-04-10}}</ref> Pleis composed and conducted the music for the 1964 film, ''[[Diary of a Bachelor]]''.<ref>{{cite book |last=Blum |first=Daniel |title=Daniel Blum's Screen World 1965 |volume=Volume 16 |publisher=Biblo & Tannen Publishers |year=1965 |isbn=0819603066}}</ref> He also composed music for the television shows ''[[Family Affair]]'' (1966), ''[[Gunsmoke]]'' (1967), ''[[The Wild Wild West]]'' (1967\u20131969), and ''[[Dusty's Trail]]'' (1973\u20131974).<ref name=\"IMDb\"/>\n\n===Later career===\nPleis arranged the songs on side one of [[Johnny Hartman]]'s 1967 album, ''I Love Everybody'', including \"[[If I Had You (1928 song)|If I Had You]]\", \"[[I Cover the Waterfront (song)|I Cover the Waterfront]]\", and \"[[For Once in My Life]]\".<ref name=Akkerman>{{cite book |first=Gregg |last=Akkerman |title=The Last Balladeer: The Johnny Hartman Story |publisher=Scarecrow Press |year=2012 |isbn=9780810882812 |pages=150\u2013151, 308}}</ref>\n\nPleis produced several of [[Harry Belafonte]]'s albums, ''[[Belafonte by Request]]'' (1970), ''[[The Warm Touch]]'' (1971), and ''[[Calypso Carnival]]'' (1971). Pleis also produced several of [[Jack Jones (singer)|Jack Jones]]' albums, ''A Jack Jones Christmas'' (1969),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.discogs.com/Jack-Jones-A-Jack-Jones-Christmas/release/3408546 |title=Jack Jones \u2013 ''A Jack Jones Christmas'' |work=Discogs |accessdate=2015-04-10}}</ref> ''A Time for Us'' (1970),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://jackjones.lolipop.jp/1970-a-time-for-us/ |title=1970: ''A Time for Us'' |work=Official Jack Jones website |accessdate=2015-04-10}}</ref> and ''Christmas With Jack Jones'' (1973).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.discogs.com/Jack-Jones-Christmas-With-Jack-Jones/release/4911631 |title= Jack Jones \u2013 ''Christmas With Jack Jones'' |work=Discogs |accessdate=2015-04-10}}</ref> He produced [[Hugo Montenegro]]'s album, ''Colours Of Love'' (1970).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.45worlds.com/vinyl/album/lsp4273 |title=Vinyl Album: Hugo Montenegro, ''Colours of Love'' |work=45worlds.com |accessdate=2015-04-10}}</ref>\n\nIn 1976, Pleis put out what would be the last album released under his own name, ''I Play the Songs the Whole World Sings'', on [[Ranwood Records]].<ref>{{cite web |first1=Mike |last1=Callahan |first2=David |last2=Edwards |url=http://www.bsnpubs.com/dot/ranwood.html |title=Ranwood Album Discography |work=Bsnpubs.com |date=November 16, 2003  |accessdate=2015-04-13}}</ref>\n\n==Private life and death==\nPleis was married to singer [[Karen Chandler]].<ref name=\"Chandler obit\">{{cite web|url=http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/lbpresstelegram/obituary.aspx?n=eva-nadauld-pleis-karen-chandler&pid=146518454 |title=Eva Nadauld (KAREN CHANDLER) Pleis Obituary |work=Los Angeles Daily News |date=November 9, 2010 |publisher=Legacy.com |accessdate=2014-09-14}}</ref> He died December 5, 1990 in [[Palm Springs, California]],<ref name=\"IMDb\"/> and is survived by his children Michelle Pleis Stirber, Jason Pleis, and Damon Pleis.<ref name=\"Chandler obit\"/>\n\n==Charted hits==\n* \"Giant\", [[Billboard charts|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], #93 (10/20/1956), #91 (12/29/1956)<ref name=\"Giant\"/>\n* \"I'll Always Be In Love With You\", ''Billboard'' Hot 100, #65 (12/08/1956)<ref name=chart2/>\n* \"(But As They Say) That's Life\", ''Billboard'' Hot 100, #69 (6/17/1957)<ref name=chart3/>\n\n==Selected discography==\n\n===Albums===\n\n====''Music from Disneyland''====\n;{{cite AV media |people=Jack Pleis and His Orchestra and Chorus |year=1955 |title=[[Music from Disneyland]] |type=LP |publisher=Decca  |id=DL 8105}}\n{{track listing |collapsed=yes\n|title1=[[When You Wish upon a Star]] |length1=2:56 |writer1=[[Leigh Harline]]/[[Ned Washington]]\n|title2=[[Heigh-Ho|Heigh-Ho - Whistle While You Work]] |length2=2:47 |writer2=[[Frank Churchill]]/[[Larry Morey]]\n|title3=[[Someday My Prince Will Come]] |note3=\"Some Day I'll Find My Love\" |length3=2:45 |writer3=[[Frank Churchill]]/[[Larry Morey]]\n|title4=[[Na Baixa do Sapateiro|Ba\u00eda]] |length4=3:27 |writer4=[[Ary Barroso]]/[[Ray Gilbert]]\n|title5=[[Who's Afraid of the Big Bad Wolf?]] |length5=3:00 |writer5=[[Frank Churchill]]/[[Ann Ronell]]\n|title6=[[Bibbidi-Bobbidi-Boo]] |note6=\"The Magic Song\" |length6=2:34 |writer6=[[Al Hoffman]]/[[Jerry Livingston]]/[[Mack David]]\n|title7=[[A Dream Is a Wish Your Heart Makes]] |length7=2:44 |writer7=[[Al Hoffman]]/[[Jerry Livingston]]/[[Mack David]]\n|title8=[[Lavender Blue]] |note8=\"Dilly, Dilly\" |length8=2:44 |writer8=Traditional\n|title9=[[Melody Time#Songs|Melody Time]] |length9=2:59 |writer9=[[George David Weiss]]/[[Bennie Benjamin]]\n|title10=[[You Belong to My Heart]] |length10=3:00 |writer10=[[Agust\u00edn Lara]]/[[Ray Gilbert]]\n|title11=[[Bambi|Love Is a Song]] |length11=3:18 |writer11=[[Frank Churchill]]/[[Larry Morey]]\n|title12=[[Zip-a-Dee-Doo-Dah]] |length12=2:21 |writer12=[[Allie Wrubel]]/[[Ray Gilbert]]\n}}\n\n====''Broadway Goes Hollywood''====\n;{{cite AV media |people=Jack Pleis, His Piano, Orchestra and Chorus |year=1955 |title=Broadway Goes Hollywood |type=LP |publisher=Decca  |id=DL 8167}}\n{{track listing |title1=[[Oh, What a Beautiful Mornin']] |writer1=[[Richard Rodgers|Rodgers]] & [[Oscar Hammerstein II|Hammerstein]]\n|title2=[[People Will Say We're in Love]] |writer2=[[Richard Rodgers|Rodgers]] & [[Oscar Hammerstein II|Hammerstein]]\n|title3=[[I Love Paris]] |writer3=[[Cole Porter]]\n|title4=[[Stranger in Paradise (song)|Stranger in Paradise]] |writer4=[[Robert Wright (writer)|Robert Wright]]/[[George Forrest (author)|George Forrest]]\n|title5=[[Hey There]] |length5=2:43 |writer5=[[Jerry Ross (composer)|Jerry Ross]]/[[Richard Adler]]\n|title6=I'll Know |writer6=[[Frank Loesser]]\n|title7=[[Hello, Young Lovers (song)|Hello, Young Lovers]] |writer7=[[Richard Rodgers|Rodgers]] & [[Oscar Hammerstein II|Hammerstein]]\n|title8=[[We Kiss in a Shadow]] |writer8=[[Richard Rodgers|Rodgers]] & [[Oscar Hammerstein II|Hammerstein]]\n|title9=[[I'm in Love with a Wonderful Guy|A Wonderful Guy]] |writer9=[[Richard Rodgers|Rodgers]] & [[Oscar Hammerstein II|Hammerstein]]\n|title10=[[Younger Than Springtime]] |writer10=[[Richard Rodgers|Rodgers]] & [[Oscar Hammerstein II|Hammerstein]]\n|title11=[[Old Devil Moon]] |writer11=[[Burton Lane]]/[[Yip Harburg]]\n|title12=[[I Get a Kick Out of You]] |writer12=[[Cole Porter]]\n}}\n\n====''Strings and Things''====\n;{{cite AV media |people=Jack Pleis, His Piano, Chorus and Orchestra |year=1957 |title=[[Strings and Things]] |type=LP |publisher=Decca  |id=DL 8422}}\n{{track listing |collapsed=yes\n|title1=Frenchman In St. Louis |length1=3:01\n|title2=The Waltz Of Tears\n|title3=For Always\n|title4=Mr. Peepers\n|title5=A Catchy Tune\n|title6=[[Beyond the Blue Horizon (song)|Beyond The Blue Horizon]] |writer6=[[Leo Robin|Robin]]/[[Richard A. Whiting|Whiting]]/[[W. Franke Harling|Harling]]\n|title7=I'll Always Be In Love With You\n|title8=Paris Loves Lovers\n|title9=Theme from ''[[The Story of Three Loves]]'', The Eighteenth Variation |writer9=[[Mikl\u00f3s R\u00f3zsa]]\n|title10=Todd\n|title11=Strings And Things |writer11=Jack Pleis<ref>{{cite news |title=Strings and Things |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=February 2, 1957 |page=30}}</ref>\n|title12=Pagan In Paris |length12=2:51\n}}\n\n====''Serenades to Remember''====\n;{{cite AV media |people=Jack Pleis, His Piano and Orchestra |year=1957 |title=Serenades to Remember |type=LP |publisher=Decca  |id=DL 8586}}\n{{track listing |title1=[[Moonlight Serenade]] |writer1=[[Glenn Miller]]/[[Mitchell Parish]]\n|title2=Serenade To Michelle |writer2=Jack Pleis{{citation needed|date=April 2015}}\n|title3=[[Sunrise Serenade]] |writer3=[[Frankie Carle]]/[[Jack Lawrence]]\n|title4=Serenade In Soft Shoe |writer4=Jack Pleis{{citation needed|date=April 2015}}\n|title5=Autumn Serenade\t|writer5=[[Peter DeRose]]/[[Sammy Gallop]]\n|title6=A Blues Serenade\t|writer6=[[Frank Signorelli]]\n|title7=[[Serenade In Blue]] |writer7=[[Harry Warren]]/[[Mack Gordon]]\n|title8=Twilight Serenade\t|writer8=Johnny Napton\n|title9=Sleepy Serenade|writer9=Lou Singer/Mort Greene\n|title10=Serenata |writer10=[[Leroy Anderson]]\n|title11=[[Sultry Serenade]] |writer11=[[Herbie Mann]]\n|title12=[[Manhattan Serenade]] |writer12=[[Louis Alter]]\n}}\n\n====''50 Memorable Melodies In Hi-Fi''====\n;{{cite AV media |people=Jack Pleis and His Orchestra |year=1958 |title=50 Memorable Melodies In Hi-Fi |type=LP |publisher=Decca  |id=DL 8706}}\n{{track listing \n|title1=I Love My Baby |note1=Medley\n|title2=Oh! My Pa-Pa |note2=Medley\n|title3=Sweetheart Of All My Dreams |note3=Medley\n|title4=Melody Of Love |note4=Medley\n|title5=Red Sails In The Sunset |note5=Medley\n|title6=Mister Sandman |note6=Medley\n|title7=Drifting And Dreaming |note7=Medley\n|title8=[[Ole Buttermilk Sky]] |note8=Medley\n|title9=Tenderly |note9=Medley\n|title10=I'll Walk Alone |note10=Medley\n}}\n\n====''Music for Two Sleepy People''====\n;{{cite AV media |people=Jack Pleis and His Orchestra |year=1958 |title=[[Music for Two Sleepy 