s.com/decca/decca/decca8000.html |title=Decca Album Discography, Part 4: Main 12-inch 8000 Series (1949-1960)\n|author=David Edwards\n|author2=Mike Callahan\n|author3=Patrice Eyries\n|author4=Randy Watts\n|author5=Tim Neely\n|last-author-amp=yes}}\n\n==Further reading==\n;Obituaries\n*{{cite journal |author=Billboard |title=[Obituary] |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=January 5, 1991 |volume=103 |page=77}}\n*{{cite journal |author=International Musician |title=Jack K. Pleis, noted arranger, composer and pianist, dead at 73 |work=[[International Musician]] |date=February 1991 |volume=89 |page=15}}\n*{{cite journal |author=Variety |title=[Obituary] |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=December 17, 1990 |volume=341 |pages=70\u201371}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://archive.org/details/JackPleisOrchestraCollection/v2 Jack Pleis Orchestra Collection] at [[Internet Archive]]\n*[http://www.45cat.com/artist/jack-pleis Jack Pleis - Discography] at 45cat.com\n*{{Allmusic|artist|jack-pleis-mn0000780013}}\n*{{Allmusic|artist|jack-pleis-his-orchestra-mn0002156988|Jack Pleis & His Orchestra}}\n*{{Discogs artist|417233-Jack-Pleis}}\n*{{IMDb name|0687132}}\n*{{itunes|au/artist/jack-pleis-and-his-orchestra/id300672771|Jack Pleis & His Orchestra}}\n;Media\n*{{YouTube|id=5VvQ0He-6sA |title=\"Goodnight Waltz\" by Jack Pleis & His Orchestra, Decca (1957)}}\n*{{YouTube|id=Ua1XdeT1Sso |title=\"Pagan In Paris\" by Jack Pleis & His Orchestra, Decca (1952)}}\n*{{YouTube|id=gryCRQ44qNc |title=\"That's Life\" by Jack Pleis & His Orchestra, Decca (1957)}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pleis, Jack}}\n[[Category:1917 births]]\n[[Category:1990 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American composers]]\n[[Category:American jazz pianists]]\n[[Category:American male pianists]]\n[[Category:American male composers]]\n[[Category:American pop pianists]]\n[[Category:Record producers from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Record producers from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Columbia Records artists]]\n[[Category:Decca Records artists]]\n[[Category:London Records artists]]\n[[Category:Musicians from New York City]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:20th-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:20th-century American pianists]]\n[[Category:Jazz musicians from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Jazz musicians from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male musicians]]\n[[Category:Male jazz musicians]]\n", "name_user": "Refcheck", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jack_Pleis"}
{"title_page": "O'Neill Tunnel", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{Infobox tunnel\n|name = Thomas P. O'Neill Jr. Tunnel\n|image = Thomas P O'Neill Jr Tunnel entrance.jpg\n|caption = The northbound entrance to the tunnel from I-93\n|location = [[Boston|Boston, Massachusetts]]\n|coordinates =\n|route = {{jct|state=MA|I|93|US|1|MA|3}}\n|status = Open\n|start = [[South Boston]]\n|end = [[Zakim Bunker Hill Bridge]]\n|startwork =\n|opened = {{start date|2003|03|29}} (northbound), December 20, 2003 (southbound)\n|close =\n|owner = [[Commonwealth of Massachusetts]]\n|operator = [[Massachusetts Department of Transportation]]\n|character =\n|construction= 1995\u20132004\n|length = {{convert|1.5|mi|km|abbr=on}}\n|lanes = 4\n|speed = {{convert|45|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}\n|hielevation =\n|lowelevation=\n|height =\n|width =\n|grade =\n}}\n\nThe '''Thomas P. \"Tip\" O'Neill Jr. Tunnel''' (colloquially '''O'Neill Tunnel''') is a highway tunnel built as part of the [[Big Dig (Boston, Massachusetts)|Big Dig]] in [[Boston]], Massachusetts. It carries the [[Central Artery]] underneath downtown Boston, and is numbered as [[Interstate 93]] (I-93), [[U.S. Route 1 in Massachusetts|U.S. Route&nbsp;1]] (US&nbsp;1), and [[Massachusetts Route 3|Route&nbsp;3]]. It roughly follows the route of the old elevated Central Artery, though the northbound entrance, at the corner of Kneeland Street and Atlantic Avenue, is somewhat east of the southbound exit (at Kneeland and Albany streets) to allow for a reconfigured interchange with the [[Massachusetts Turnpike]]. It runs from the [[Zakim Bunker Hill Bridge]] at its north portal\u2014barely {{convert|165|ft|m}} east of the [[TD Garden]] sports facility's eastern corner\u2014to Boston's [[Chinatown (Boston)|Chinatown]] at its south portal. The tunnel is named for [[Tip O'Neill]], former [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives]].\n\n==History==\nPlanning for the tunnel began in the mid-1980s, when it was determined that a replacement for the Central Artery was needed. Originally built for 75,000 vehicles a day, the expressway was carrying 200,000 vehicles a day by the early 1990s. It was even projected that, by 2010, there would be 16-hour daily traffic jams that would cost the local economy $500 million annually. Furthermore, the [[North End, Boston|North End]] was cut off from the rest of the city, which hampered economic growth.<ref name=MassDOT>{{cite web |author = Highway Division |date = n.d. |title = Project Background |url = http://www.massdot.state.ma.us/highway/thebigdig/projectbackground.aspx |publisher = [[Massachusetts Department of Transportation]] |accessdate = September 2, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nOne challenge for building the tunnel was constructing the project underneath the existing expressway, as well as crippling the city due to the amount of construction involved.<ref name=MassDOT /> In 1992, construction began on the tunnel, with the relocation of utilities. This was followed in 1996 by the beginning of construction on the tunnels with the pouring of slurry to build walls,<ref name=MassDOT2>{{cite web |author = Highway Division |date = n.d. |title = The Big Dig |url = http://www.massdot.state.ma.us/highway/thebigdig.aspx |publisher = Massachusetts Department of Transportation |accessdate = September 2, 2014 }}</ref> which was preceded by underpinning the expressway.<ref name=MassDOT3>{{cite web |author = Highway Division |date = n.d. |title = Tunnels and Bridges |url = http://www.massdot.state.ma.us/highway/TheBigDig/TunnelsBridges.aspx#i93 |publisher = Massachusetts Department of Transportation |accessdate = September 2, 2014 }}</ref> The northbound portion of the tunnel was opened in March 2003, followed by the opening of the southbound section in December of the same year. The renovated [[Dewey Square Tunnel]], which was eventually incorporated into the O'Neill Tunnel, was opened in 2005.<ref name=MassDOT2 />\n\nIn March 2003, Massachusetts Governor [[Mitt Romney]] proposed to name the tunnel the \"Liberty Tunnel\". The state legislature and the Massachusetts delegation to [[United States Congress|Congress]] opposed the choice, and it was officially named after O'Neill (a longtime [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives]]) by Section 1930 of the [[SAFETEA-LU|Safe, Accountable, Flexible, Efficient Transportation Equity Act: A Legacy for Users (SAFETEA-LU)]], which was passed by Congress and signed by then-President [[George W. Bush]] in 2005.<ref name=Brown-West>{{cite book |last1 = Brown-West |first1 = Orikaye |title = From Dream to Reality: Scaling the Construction Planning Hurdles of a Megaproject |date = 2008 |publisher = Lulu |location = [S.l.] |isbn = 055700747X |pages = 64\u201365 |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=eDs66DV7bGQC&pg=PA64&lpg=PA64 |accessdate = September 2, 2014 |via = [[Google Books]] }}</ref>\n\nWithin a year of opening, a large leak backed up traffic for miles, which led to more investigation into leaks that were occurring within the structure. Due to the location of the tunnel near the ocean, brackish water was able to seep into cracks within the concrete, which have had the potential to cause flooding. This was also due to the purposeful design of the concrete to withstand 50-degree temperature swings, instead of the actual 100-degree swings that are experienced in Boston. In 2007, there were 500 leaks that needed to be repaired.<ref name=USAToday>{{cite news |title = 500 Leaks Await Repair in Boston Tunnels |url = http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/nation/2007-08-22-big-dig_N.htm |accessdate = September 2, 2014 |agency = [[Associated Press]] |work = [[USA Today]] |date = August 22, 2007 }}</ref> Corrosion of the tunnel light fixtures also became a problem as well, which was evidenced in 2011 when a light fixture crashed down onto the roadway. Between fixing the leaks and fixing corroded structures, a report in 2011 estimated that the costs could run a few hundred million dollars.<ref name=MurphyAllen>{{cite news |last1 = Murphy |first1 = Sean P. |last2 = Allen |first2 = Scott |title = Report Cites Costs, Risks of Big Dig Leaks |url = http://www.boston.com/news/local/massachusetts/articles/2011/07/24/report_cites_costs_risks_of_big_dig_leaks/?page=full |accessdate = September 2, 2014 |work = [[The Boston Globe]] |date = July 24, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* {{Portal-inline|United States}}\n* [[Transportation in Boston]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commons category-inline|Thomas P. O'Neill Jr. Tunnel}}\n\n{{coord|42|21|28|N|71|3|06|W|type:landmark_region:US|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thomas P. O'neill Jr. Tunnel}}\n[[Category:Tunnels in Boston]]\n[[Category:Interstate 93]]\n[[Category:U.S. Route 1]]\n[[Category:Road tunnels in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Tunnels completed in 2003]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{Infobox tunnel\n|name = Thomas P. O'Neill Jr. Tunnel\n|image = Thomas P O'Neill Jr Tunnel entrance.jpg\n|caption = The northbound entrance to the tunnel from I-93\n|location = [[Boston|Boston, Massachusetts]]\n|coordinates =\n|route = {{jct|state=MA|I|93|US|1|MA|3}}\n|status = Open\n|start = [[South Boston]]\n|end = [[Zakim Bunker Hill Bridge]]\n|startwork =\n|opened = {{start date|2003|03|29}} (northbound), December 20, 2003 (southbound)\n|close =\n|owner = [[Commonwealth of Massachusetts]]\n|operator = [[Massachusetts Department of Transportation]]\n|character =\n|construction= 1995\u20132004\n|length = {{convert|1.5|mi|km|abbr=on}}\n|lanes = 4\n|speed = {{convert|45|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}\n|hielevation =\n|lowelevation=\n|height =\n|width =\n|grade =\n}}\n\nThe '''Thomas P. \"Tip\" O'Neill Jr. Tunnel''' (colloquially '''O'Neill Tunnel''') is a highway tunnel built as part of the [[Big Dig (Boston, Massachusetts)|Big Dig]] in [[Boston]], Massachusetts. It carries the [[Central Artery]] underneath downtown Boston, and is numbered as [[Interstate 93]] (I-93), [[U.S. Route 1 in Massachusetts|U.S. Route&nbsp;1]] (US&nbsp;1), and [[Massachusetts Route 3|Route&nbsp;3]]. It roughly follows the route of the old elevated Central Artery, though the northbound entrance, at the corner of Kneeland Street and Atlantic Avenue, is somewhat east of the southbound exit (at Kneeland and Albany streets) to allow for a reconfigured interchange with the [[Massachusetts Turnpike]]. It runs from the [[Zakim Bunker Hill Bridge]] at its north portal\u2014barely {{convert|165|ft|m}} east of the [[TD Garden]] sports facility's eastern corner\u2014to Boston's [[Chinatown (Boston)|Chinatown]] at its south portal. The tunnel is named for [[Tip O'Neill]], former [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives]].\n\n==History==\nPlanning for the tunnel began in the mid-1980s, when it was determined that a replacement for the Central Artery was needed. Originally built for 75,000 vehicles a day, the expressway was carrying 200,000 vehicles a day by the early 1990s. It was even projected that, by 2010, there would be 16-hour daily traffic jams that would cost the local economy $500 million annually. Furthermore, the [[North End, Boston|North End]] was cut off from the rest of the city, which hampered economic growth.<ref name=MassDOT>{{cite web |author = Highway Division |date = n.d. |title = Project Background |url = http://www.massdot.state.ma.us/highway/thebigdig/projectbackground.aspx |publisher = [[Massachusetts Department of Transportation]] |accessdate = September 2, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nOne challenge for building the tunnel was constructing the project underneath the existing expressway, as well as crippling the city due to the amount of construction involved.<ref name=MassDOT /> In 1992, construction began on the tunnel, with the relocation of utilities. This was followed in 1996 by the beginning of construction on the tunnels with the pouring of slurry to build walls,<ref name=MassDOT2>{{cite web |author = Highway Division |date = n.d. |title = The Big Dig |url = http://www.massdot.state.ma.us/highway/thebigdig.aspx |publisher = Massachusetts Department of Transportation |accessdate = September 2, 2014 }}</ref> which was preceded by underpinning the expressway.<ref name=MassDOT3>{{cite web |author = Highway Division |date = n.d. |title = Tunnels and Bridges |url = http://www.massdot.state.ma.us/highway/TheBigDig/TunnelsBridges.aspx#i93 |publisher = Massachusetts Department of Transportation |accessdate = September 2, 2014 }}</ref> The northbound portion of the tunnel was opened in March 2003, followed by the opening of the southbound section in December of the same year. The renovated [[Dewey Square Tunnel]], which was eventually incorporated into the O'Neill Tunnel was opened in 2005.<ref name=MassDOT2 />\n\nIn March 2003, Massachusetts Governor [[Mitt Romney]] proposed to name the tunnel the \"Liberty Tunnel\". The state legislature and the Massachusetts delegation to [[United States Congress|Congress]] opposed the choice, and it was officially named after O'Neill (a longtime [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives]]) by Section 1930 of the [[SAFETEA-LU|Safe, Accountable, Flexible, Efficient Transportation Equity Act: A Legacy for Users (SAFETEA-LU)]], which was passed by Congress and signed by then-President [[George W. Bush]] in 2005.<ref name=Brown-West>{{cite book |last1 = Brown-West |first1 = Orikaye |title = From Dream to Reality: Scaling the Construction Planning Hurdles of a Megaproject |date = 2008 |publisher = Lulu |location = [S.l.] |isbn = 055700747X |pages = 64\u201365 |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=eDs66DV7bGQC&pg=PA64&lpg=PA64 |accessdate = September 2, 2014 |via = [[Google Books]] }}</ref>\n\nWithin a year of opening, a large leak backed up traffic for miles, which led to more investigation into leaks that were occurring within the structure. Due to the location of the tunnel near the ocean, brackish water was able to seep into cracks within the concrete, which have had the potential to cause flooding. This was also due to the purposeful design of the concrete to withstand 50-degree temperature swings, instead of the actual 100-degree swings that are experienced in Boston. In 2007, there were 500 leaks that needed to be repaired.<ref name=USAToday>{{cite news |title = 500 Leaks Await Repair in Boston Tunnels |url = http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/nation/2007-08-22-big-dig_N.htm |accessdate = September 2, 2014 |agency = [[Associated Press]] |work = [[USA Today]] |date = August 22, 2007 }}</ref> Corrosion of the tunnel light fixtures also became a problem as well, which was evidenced in 2011 when a light fixture crashed down onto the roadway. Between fixing the leaks and fixing corroded structures, a report in 2011 estimated that the costs could run a few hundred million dollars.<ref name=MurphyAllen>{{cite news |last1 = Murphy |first1 = Sean P. |last2 = Allen |first2 = Scott |title = Report Cites Costs, Risks of Big Dig Leaks |url = http://www.boston.com/news/local/massachusetts/articles/2011/07/24/report_cites_costs_risks_of_big_dig_leaks/?page=full |accessdate = September 2, 2014 |work = [[The Boston Globe]] |date = July 24, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* {{Portal-inline|United States}}\n* [[Transportation in Boston]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commons category-inline|Thomas P. O'Neill Jr. Tunnel}}\n\n{{coord|42|21|28|N|71|3|06|W|type:landmark_region:US|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thomas P. O'neill Jr. Tunnel}}\n[[Category:Tunnels in Boston]]\n[[Category:Interstate 93]]\n[[Category:U.S. Route 1]]\n[[Category:Road tunnels in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Tunnels completed in 2003]]\n", "name_user": "Julietdeltalima", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:punctuation correction", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/O%27Neill_Tunnel"}
