 2020 events in China]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in China]]\n[[Category:Occupational safety and health]]\n[[Category:Pandemics]]\n[[Category:Pandemics with high degree of misinformation]]\n[[Category:Public Health Emergency of International Concern]]\n", "name_user": "-sche", "label": "safe", "comment": "restore oxford spelling - see talk page - this was mistakenly changed by someone", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2019%E2%80%9320_coronavirus_pandemic"}
{"title_page": "James Vernon the Younger", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2017}}\n[[File:James Vernon.jpg|thumb|James Vernon the Younger in the 1690s]]\n\n'''James Vernon the Younger''' (15 June 1677 \u2013 17 April 1756) was a British government official, courtier, diplomat and Whig politician who sat in the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] from 1708 to 1710. He was an envoy to Denmark from 1702 to 1707.\n\n==Early life==\nVernon was the eldest son of [[James Vernon]] and his wife Mary Buck, daughter of Sir John Buck, 1st Baronet, of Hamby Grange, Lincolnshire. His father was [[Secretary of State (England)|Secretary of State]] under [[William III of England|William III]]. He was educated at Utrecht in 1690, at Rotterdam from 1690 to 1692 and a Utrecht again from 1696 to 1697.<ref name = HOP>{{cite web| url = http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1690-1715/member/vernon-james-ii-1677-1756| title=VERNON, James II (1677-1756), of Westminster, Mdx. | publisher= History of Parliament Online| accessdate = 4 June 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIn 1691, Vernon was appointed serjeant of the chandlery. He was appointed an extra clerk of the [[Her Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council]] in 1697. His first parliamentary attempt was in a by-election in 1698 at [[Penryn (UK Parliament constituency)|Penryn]] when he was unsuccessful. He was groom of bedchamber to Duke of Gloucester from 1698 to 1700. From his close attendance on the Duke he contracted the illness from which the Duke died, and took several months to recover. At the second general election of 1701, he and his father contested [[St Mawes (UK Parliament constituency)|St Mawes]], but were unable to overcome the established interest. From 1701 to 1702 he was a Commissioner of the privy seal. In May 1702, he was elected a [[Fellow of the Royal Society]].<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www2.royalsociety.org/DServe/dserve.exe?dsqIni=Dserve.ini&dsqApp=Archive&dsqCmd=Show.tcl&dsqDb=Persons&dsqPos=3&dsqSearch=%28Surname%3D%27vernon%27%29 | title= Library and Archive Catalogue | publisher= Royal Society | accessdate= 29 October 2010 }}{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He served as [[List of Ambassadors from the United Kingdom to Denmark|British envoy to Denmark]] from 1702 to 1707<ref>[http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/catalogue/default.asp?j=1 The National Archives Catalogue], SP75/24-25</ref> and was groom of bedchamber to the Prince of Denmark from 1702 to 1708.<ref name=HOP/>\n\nAt the [[1708 British general election]] Vernon was returned as Whig [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Cricklade (UK Parliament constituency)|Cricklade]]. In early 1709 he supported the naturalization of the Palatines, and in 1710 voted for the impeachment of Dr Sacheverell, later airing his dismay that Whig leaders had made such a fuss about \u2018a factious preacher much below their notice\u2019. He became a Commissioner for excise in 1710, in compensation for his father's dismissal as teller of the Exchequer. The post, worth \u00a3800 a year, made him ineligible to stand at the [[1710 British general election]].\n\n==Later life==\nVernon disentangled himself from politics and chose to serve the Tory administration as an official. In 1713, he married Arethusa Boyle daughter of [[Charles Boyle, Lord Clifford]] of Lanesborough. When King George I came to the throne in 1714 and the Whigs were in power his Whig background served him and he not only kept his post but was also appointed a [[Clerk of the Privy Council (United Kingdom)|Clerk of the Privy Council]] in 1715, which he held for the rest of his life.<ref>[http://www.history.ac.uk/resources/office/privycounc-alpha Officeholders in modern England.]</ref> In 1716 he was again Commissioner of the Privy Seal.<ref name=HOP/> He lost his post at the Excise in 1726 after a disagreement with Walpole, but it was restored in 1728. In 1727 he succeeded his father, but his wife died in 1728.<ref name=HOP/>\n\nVernon devoted his efforts to religious and charitable works. He was a sponsor of the foundation of Georgia and a trustee for Bray's charity. His government duties kept him in London, but by 1733 he had purchased an estate at Great Thurlow, Suffolk, for \u00a315,000. Later he built workhouses for several Suffolk parishes. He died without issue on 15 or 17 April 1756, and was buried at Great Thurlow.<ref name=HOP/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-dip}}\n{{s-bef|before= [[Hugh Greg]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title= [[List of Ambassadors from the United Kingdom to Denmark|British envoy to Denmark]] |years= 1702&ndash;1707 }}\n{{s-aft|after= [[Daniel Pulteney]]}}\n{{s-par|gb}}\n{{s-bef|before= [[Samuel Barker (MP for Cricklade)|Samuel Barker]] | before2=[[Edmund Dunch (Whig)|Edmund Dunch]] }}\n{{s-ttl|title= [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Cricklade (UK Parliament constituency)|Cricklade]] |with= [[Edmund Dunch (Whig)|Edmund Dunch]] |years= 1708&ndash;1710 }}\n{{s-aft|after= [[Samuel Robinson (1666-1729)|Samuel Robinson]] | after2=[[Edmund Dunch (Whig)|Edmund Dunch]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vernon, James, The Younger}}\n[[Category:British MPs 1708\u20131710]]\n[[Category:English civil servants]]\n[[Category:1677 births]]\n[[Category:1756 deaths]]\n[[Category:Clerks of the Privy Council]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of England to Denmark]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Great Britain for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Members of Parliament for Cricklade]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2017}}\n[[File:James Vernon.jpg|thumb|James Vernon the Younger in the 1690s]]\n\n'''James Vernon the Younger''' (15 June 1677 \u2013 17 April 1756) was a British government official, courtier, diplomat and Whig politician who sat in the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] from 1708 to 1710. He was an envoy to Denmark from 1702 to 1707.\n\n==Early life==\nVernon was the eldest son of [[James Vernon]] and his wife Mary Buck, daughter of Sir John Buck, 1st Baronet, of Hamby Grange, Lincolnshire. His father was [[Secretary of State (England)|Secretary of State]] under [[William III of England|William III]]. He was educated at Utrecht in 1690, at Rotterdam from 1690 to 1692 and a Utrecht again from 1696 to 1697.<ref name = HOP>{{cite web| url = http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1690-1715/member/vernon-james-ii-1677-1756| title=VERNON, James II (1677-1756), of Westminster, Mdx. | publisher= History of Parliament Online| accessdate = 4 June 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIn 1691, Vernon was appointed serjeant of the chandlery. He was appointed an extra clerk of the [[Her Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council]] in 1697. His first parliamentary attempt was in a by-election in 1698 at [[Penryn (UK Parliament constituency)|Penryn]] when he was unsuccessful. He was groom of bedchamber to Duke of Gloucester from 1698 to 1700. From his close attendance on the Duke he contracted the illness from which the Duke died, and took several months to recover. At the second general election of 1701, he and his father contested [[St Mawes (UK Parliament constituency)|St Mawes]], but were unable to overcome the established interest. From 1701 to 1702 he was a Commissioner of the privy seal. In May 1702, he was elected a [[Fellow of the Royal Society]].<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www2.royalsociety.org/DServe/dserve.exe?dsqIni=Dserve.ini&dsqApp=Archive&dsqCmd=Show.tcl&dsqDb=Persons&dsqPos=3&dsqSearch=%28Surname%3D%27vernon%27%29 | title= Library and Archive Catalogue | publisher= Royal Society | accessdate= 29 October 2010 }}{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He served as [[List of Ambassadors from the United Kingdom to Denmark|British envoy to Denmark]] from 1702 to 1707<ref>[http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/catalogue/default.asp?j=1 The National Archives Catalogue], SP75/24-25</ref> and was groom of bedchamber to the Prince of Denmark from 1702 to 1708.<ref name=HOP/>\n\nAt the [[1708 British general election]] Vernon was returned as Whig [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Cricklade (UK Parliament constituency)|Cricklade]]. In early 1709 he supported the naturalization of the Palatines, and in 1710 voted for the impeachment of Dr Sacheverell, later airing his dismay that Whig leaders had made such a fuss about \u2018a factious preacher much below their notice\u2019. He became a Commissioner for excise in 1710, in compensation for his father\u2019s dismissal as teller of the Exchequer. The post, worth \u00a3800 a year, made him ineligible to stand at the [[1710 British general election]].\n\n==Later life==\nVernon disentangled himself from politics and chose to serve the Tory administration as an official. In 1713, he married Arethusa Boyle daughter of [[Charles Boyle, Lord Clifford]] of Lanesborough. When King George I came to the throne in 1714 and the Whigs were in power his Whig background served him and he not only kept his post but was also appointed a [[Clerk of the Privy Council (United Kingdom)|Clerk of the Privy Council]] in 1715, which he held for the rest of his life.<ref>[http://www.history.ac.uk/resources/office/privycounc-alpha Officeholders in modern England.]</ref> In 1716 he was again Commissioner of the Privy Seal.<ref name=HOP/> He lost his post at the Excise in 1726 after a disagreement with Walpole, but it was restored in 1728. In 1727 he succeeded his father, but his wife died in 1728.<ref name=HOP/>\n\nVernon devoted his efforts to religious and charitable works. He was a sponsor of the foundation of Georgia and a trustee for Bray\u2019s charity. His government duties kept him in London, but by 1733 he had purchased an estate at Great Thurlow, Suffolk, for \u00a315,000. Later he built workhouses for several Suffolk parishes. He died without issue on 15 or 17 April 1756, and was buried at Great Thurlow.<ref name=HOP/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-dip}}\n{{s-bef|before= [[Hugh Greg]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title= [[List of Ambassadors from the United Kingdom to Denmark|British envoy to Denmark]] |years= 1702&ndash;1707 }}\n{{s-aft|after= [[Daniel Pulteney]]}}\n{{s-par|gb}}\n{{s-bef|before= [[Samuel Barker (MP for Cricklade)|Samuel Barker]] | before2=[[Edmund Dunch (Whig)|Edmund Dunch]] }}\n{{s-ttl|title= [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Cricklade (UK Parliament constituency)|Cricklade]] |with= [[Edmund Dunch (Whig)|Edmund Dunch]] |years= 1708&ndash;1710 }}\n{{s-aft|after= [[Samuel Robinson (1666-1729)|Samuel Robinson]] | after2=[[Edmund Dunch (Whig)|Edmund Dunch]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vernon, James, The Younger}}\n[[Category:British MPs 1708\u20131710]]\n[[Category:English civil servants]]\n[[Category:1677 births]]\n[[Category:1756 deaths]]\n[[Category:Clerks of the Privy Council]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of England to Denmark]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Great Britain for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Members of Parliament for Cricklade]]\n", "name_user": "J947", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Vernon_the_Younger"}
